s://web.archive.org/web/20140629170901/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=61&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374164893234&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2575|archive-date=29 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| population_blank2               = {{Collapsible list\n|title                   = 93.05% [[White people|White]]\n|frame_style             = border:none; padding: 0;\n|list_style              = text-align:left;display:none;\n|3                       = 88.32% [[White British]]\n|4                       = 0.53% [[Irish Briton|White Irish]]\n|5                       = 0.08% [[Romani people|Gypsy]] or [[Irish Travellers|Irish Traveller]]\n|6                       = 4.12% [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|Other White]]\n|7                       = &nbsp;\n|8                       = '''1.65% [[British Mixed|Mixed]]'''\n|9                       = 0.34% [[British Mixed|White & Black Caribbean]]\n|10                      = 0.24% [[British Mixed|White & Black African]]\n|11                      = 0.66% [[British Mixed|White and Asian]]\n|12                      = 0.41% [[British Mixed|Other mixed]]\n|13                      = &nbsp;\n|14                      = '''3.90% [[British Asian|Asian]]'''\n|15                      = 0.80% [[Indian British|Indian]]\n|16                      = 0.14% [[Pakistani British|Pakistani]]\n|17                      = 0.19% [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]]\n|18                      = 1.70% [[British Chinese|Chinese]]\n|19                      = 1.07% [[British Asian|Other Asian]]\n|20                      = &nbsp;\n|21                      = '''0.57% [[Black British|Black]]'''\n|22                      = 0.42% [[African British|Black African]]\n|23                      = 0.11% [[British African-Caribbean community|Black Caribbean]]\n|24                      = 0.04% [[Black British|Other Black]]\n|25                      = &nbsp;\n|26                      = '''0.83% [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|Other]]'''\n|27                      = 0.56% [[British Arabs|Arab]]\n|28                      = 0.28% [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|Other]]\n}}\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{United Kingdom district population citation|England}}</ref>\n| timezone                        = [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]\n| utc_offset                      = 0\n| timezone_DST                    = [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = +1\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|50|43|N|3|32|W|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in the United Kingdom|Postcode district]]\n| postal_code                     = [[EX postcode area|EX1-6]]\n| area_code                       = 01392\n| website                         = {{URL|https://exeter.gov.uk}}\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Exeter''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Exeter.ogg|\u02c8|\u025b|k|s|\u026a|t|\u0259r}}) is a city in [[Devon]], [[England]], on the [[River Exe]] {{convert|36|mi|km}} northeast of [[Plymouth]] and {{convert|65|mi|km}} southwest of [[Bristol]]. It is the [[county town]] of Devon, and home to [[Devon County Council]] and the [[University of Exeter]].\n\nIn [[Roman Britain]], Exeter was established as the base of [[Legio II Augusta]] under the personal command of [[Vespasian]]. Exeter became a religious centre in the [[Middle Ages]]. [[Exeter Cathedral]], founded in the mid 11th century, became [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] in the 16th-century [[English Reformation]]. In the late 19th century, Exeter became an affluent centre for the [[wool trade]], although by the [[First World War]] the city was in decline. After the [[Second World War]], much of the city centre was rebuilt and is now a centre for business and tourism in Devon and Cornwall.\n\nThe administrative area of Exeter has the status of a [[non-metropolitan district]] under the administration of the County Council; a plan to grant the city [[unitary authority]] status was scrapped by the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|2010 coalition government]].\n\n==Name==\nThe modern name of Exeter is a development of the [[Old English]] ''Escanceaster'',<ref name=tcodoepn>{{cite book |title=The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names |author=Eilert Ekwall |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1981 |page=171 |isbn=0-19-869103-3}}</ref> from the [[Anglicization of names|anglicised]] form of the river now known as the [[River Exe|Exe]] and the Old English [[suffix]] {{nowrap|[[Chester (placename element)|-''ceaster'']]}} (as in [[Dorset#Toponymy|Dorset]] and [[Gloucester#Etymology|Glowcester]]), used to mark important fortresses or fortified towns. (The Welsh name for the city, {{lang|cy|Caerwysg}}, similarly means \"[[caer|''caer'' or fortress]] on the Exe\".) The name \"Exe\" is a separate development of the [[Common Brittonic|Brittonic]] name&mdash;meaning \"water\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names |author=Eilert Ekwall |publisher=OUP |location=Oxford [Eng.] |year=1981 |pages=171 |isbn=0-19-869103-3}}</ref> or, more exactly, \"full of fish\" (cf. [[Welsh language|Welsh]] ''pysg'', {{abbr|pl.|Plural}} \"fish\")<ref>Owen, H.W. & Morgan, R. 2007 Dictionary of the Place-names of Wales Gomer Press, Ceredigion; Gwasg Gomer / Gomer Press; page 484.</ref>&mdash;that also appears in the [[England|English]] [[River Axe (Lyme Bay)|Axe]] and [[River Esk, North Yorkshire|Esk]] and the [[Wales|Welsh]] [[River Usk|Usk]] ({{lang-cy|Wysg}}).\n\n==History==\n{{Further|Timeline of Exeter}}\n\n===Prehistory===\n{{see also|Dumnonii|British Iron Age}}\nExeter began as settlements on a dry ridge ending in a spur overlooking a navigable [[River Exe|river]] teeming with fish, with fertile land nearby. Although there have been no major [[Prehistoric Britain|prehistoric]] finds, these advantages suggest the site was occupied early.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 4\u2013}}5.</ref> [[Numismatics|Coins]] have been discovered from the [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic kingdoms]], suggesting the existence of a settlement trading with the Mediterranean as early as {{nowrap|250 {{sc|bc}}}}.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|p. 1.}}</ref> Such early towns had been a feature of pre-Roman [[Gaul]] as described by [[Julius Caesar]] in his ''[[Commentarii de Bello Gallico|Commentaries]]'' and it is possible that they existed in [[Britannia]] as well.\n[[File:Door through the city walls - geograph.org.uk - 809408.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A portion of Exeter's city wall, formed of both Roman and medieval stones.]]\n\n===Roman times===\n{{Main|Isca Dumnoniorum|Legio II Augusta|Roman Britain}}\nThe [[Ancient Romans|Romans]] established a {{convert|42|acre|ha|adj=on}} 'playing-card' shaped (rectangle with round corners and two short and two long sides) fort ({{lang-la|[[castrum]]}}) named '''[[Isca Dumnoniorum|Isca]]''' around {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;55. The fort was the southwest terminus of the [[Fosse Way]] (Route 15 of the ''[[Antonine Itinerary]]'') and served as the base of the {{nowrap|5&thinsp;000-}}man [[Legio II Augusta|Second Augustan Legion]] ({{lang|la|Legio II Augusta}}) originally led by Vespasian, later Roman Emperor, for the next 20 years before they moved to [[Caerleon]] in [[Wales]], which was also known as [[Isca Augusta|Isca]]. To distinguish the two, the Romans also referred to Exeter as {{nowrap|'''Isca Dumnoniorum'''}}, \"Watertown of the [[Dumnonii]]\", and Caerleon as Isca Augusta. A small fort was also maintained at [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]]; a supply depot on the route between the two was excavated at {{nowrap|St Loyes}} on Topsham Road in 2010.\n\nThe presence of the fort built up an unplanned civilian community ({{lang|la|[[vicus]]}} or {{lang|la|[[canabae]]}}) of [[Britons (Celtic people)|natives]] and the soldiers' families, mostly to the northeast of the fort. This settlement served as the [[civitas|tribal capital]] ({{lang|la|civitas}}) of the [[Dumnonii]]<ref name=bidy>Bidwell, Paul&nbsp;T. ''Roman Exeter: Fortress and Town'', {{nowrap|p.&nbsp;56}}. Exeter City Council (Exeter), 1980. {{ISBN|0-86114-270-5}}.</ref> and was listed as one of their four cities ({{lang-grc-gre|[[poleis]]|script=Latn}}) by [[Claudius Ptolemy|Ptolemy]] in his ''[[Geography (Ptolemy)|Geography]]''<ref name=RBOD>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-britain.org/tribes/dumnonii.htm|title=The Celtic Tribes of Britain: The Dumnonii|publisher=Roman Britain Organisation|accessdate=5 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708032030/http://www.roman-britain.org/tribes/dumnonii.htm|archive-date=8 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> (it also appeared in the 7th-century ''[[Ravenna Cosmography]]'', where it appears as an apparently [[scribal error|confused]] entry for {{lang|la|Scadu Namorum}}<ref name=RBOID>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-britain.org/places/isca_dumnoniorum.htm|title=isca dvmnoniorvm|publisher=Roman Britain Organisation|accessdate=5 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512150808/http://www.roman-britain.org/places/isca_dumnoniorum.htm|archivedate=12 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>). When the fortress was abandoned around the year 75, its grounds were converted to civilian purposes: its very large [[thermae|bathhouse]] was demolished to make way for a [[forum (Roman)|forum]] and a [[basilica]], and a smaller-scale bath was erected to the southeast.<ref name=bidy/> This area was excavated in the 1970s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britarch.ac.uk/ba/ba65/feat2.shtml|title=Great Sites: Exeter Roman Baths|work=British Archaeology magazine|date=June 2002|accessdate=12 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200646/http://www.britarch.ac.uk/ba/ba65/feat2.shtml|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/timetrail/02_romanfortress/bath_house.htm |title=The Roman Fortress at Exeter: the Roman Bath House|accessdate=12 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080604101008/http://www.exeter.gov.uk/timetrail/02_romanfortress/bath_house.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 4 June 2008}}</ref> but could not be maintained for public view owing to its proximity to the [[Exeter Cathedral|present-day cathedral]]. In January 2015, it was announced that Exeter Cathedral had launched a bid to restore the baths and open an underground centre for visitors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-30081921 |title=Excavation plans for Exeter's Roman Baths |last=Jones |first=Claire |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=16 January 2015 |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109221622/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-30081921 |archive-date=9 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2nd century, the ditch and rampart defences around the old fortress were replaced by a bank and wall enclosing a much larger area, some 92&nbsp;acres (37&nbsp;ha).<ref name=B59>Bidwell (1980), {{nowrap|p. 59}}.</ref> Although most of the visible structure is older, the course of the Roman wall was used for Exeter's subsequent city walls. Thus about 70% of the Roman wall remains, and most of its route can be traced on foot. The Devonian Isca seems to have been most prosperous in the first half of the 4th century: more than a thousand [[Roman coins]] have been found around the city and there is evidence for copper and bronze working, a stock-yard, and markets for the livestock, crops, and pottery produced in the surrounding countryside.<ref>Bidwell (1980), {{nowrap|pp. 69\u2013}}76 & 80.</ref> The dating of the coins so far discovered, however, suggests a rapid decline: virtually none have been discovered dated after the year 380.<ref>Hoskins, William George. ''Two Thousand Years in Exeter'', rev. ed., {{nowrap|p. 14}}. Phillimore (Chicester), 2004. {{ISBN|1-86077-303-6}}.</ref>\n\n===Medieval times===\n{{see also|Sub-Roman Britain|Saxon England|Norman England}}\n[[Bishop Ussher]] identified the [[caer|Cair]] {{nowrap|Pensa ''vel'' Coyt}}<ref name=mommy>[[Nennius]] ({{abbr|attrib.|Traditional attribution}}). [[Theodor Mommsen]] ({{abbr|ed.|Editor}}). [[s:la:Historia Brittonum#VI. CIVITATES BRITANNIAE|''Historia Brittonum'', VI.]] Composed after {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;830. {{in lang|la}} Hosted at [[s:la:Main Page|Latin Wikisource]].</ref> listed among the 28 [[civitas|cities]] of [[Sub-Roman Britain|Britain]] by the ''[[Historia Brittonum|History of the Britons]]'' as Isca,<ref name=shusher>Newman, John Henry &&nbsp;al. [http://www.mocavo.co.uk/Lives-of-the-English-Saints-St-Gilbert-Prior-of-Sempringham-Volume-3/527392/459 ''Lives of the English Saints: St. German, Bishop of Auxerre'', Ch.&nbsp;X: \"Britain in 429, A.&nbsp;D.\",<!--sic--> p.&nbsp;92.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321234154/http://www.mocavo.co.uk/Lives-of-the-English-Saints-St-Gilbert-Prior-of-Sempringham-Volume-3/527392/459 |date=21 March 2016 }} James Toovey (London), 1844.</ref> although David Nash Ford read it as a reference to [[Penselwood]] and thought it more likely to be [[Lindinis]] (modern [[Ilchester]]).<ref name=nashford>Ford, David Nash. \"[http://www.britannia.com/history/ebk/articles/nenniuscities.html The 28 Cities of Britain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415120312/http://www.britannia.com/history/ebk/articles/nenniuscities.html |date=15 April 2016 }}\" at Britannia. 2000.</ref> Nothing is certainly known of Exeter from the time of the [[Roman withdrawal from Britain]] around the year 410 until the seventh century.<ref name=\"HOS15\">Hoskins 2004, p. 15</ref> By that time, the city was held by the [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxons]], who had arrived in Exeter after defeating the [[Britons (Celtic people)|British]] [[Dumnonia]]ns at [[Battle of Peonnum|Peonnum]] in [[Somerset]] in 658.<ref>Sellman (1985), {{nowrap|p. 16}}.</ref> It seems likely that the Saxons maintained a quarter of the city for the Britons under their own laws around present-day Bartholomew Street,<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 15\u2013}}16.</ref> which was known as \"Britayne\" Street until 1637 in memory of its former occupants.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|p. 159}}.</ref>\n\nExeter was known to the Saxons as '''Escanceaster'''.<ref name=tcodoepn/> In 876, it was [[Viking invasions of England|attacked and briefly captured]] by [[Danes (ancient people)|Danish]] [[Vikings]]. [[Alfred the Great]] drove them out the next summer.<ref name=\"HOS23\"/> Over the next few years, he elevated Exeter to one of the four ''[[burh]]s'' in Devon, rebuilding its walls on the Roman lines.<ref name=\"SEL17\">Sellman (1985), {{nowrap|p. 17}}.</ref> These permitted the city to fend off another attack and siege by the Danes in 893.<ref name=\"SEL17\"/> [[Athelstan of England|King Athelstan]] again strengthened the walls around 928, and at the same time drove out the remaining [[Britons (historical)|Britons]] from the city.<ref name=\"HOS23\">Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|p. 23}}.</ref> (It is uncertain, though, whether they had lived in the city continuously since the Roman period or returned from the countryside when Alfred strengthened its defences.<ref>Higham (2008), {{nowrap|p. 47}}.</ref>) According to [[William of Malmesbury]], they were sent beyond the [[River Tamar]], which was fixed as the boundary of Devon. (This may, however, have served as a territorial boundary within the former kingdom of [[Dumnonia]] as well.<ref>Higham (2008), {{nowrap|p. 19}}.</ref>) Other references suggest that the British simply moved to what is now the {{nowrap|St. David's}} area, not far outside Exeter's walls. The quarter vacated by the Britons was apparently adapted as \"the [[earl]]'s burh\" and was still named Irlesberi in the 12th century.<ref name=\"HOS23\"/> In 1001, the Danes again failed to get into the city, but they were able to plunder it in 1003 because they were let in, for unknown reasons, by the [[Kingdom of France|French]] [[Reeve (England)|reeve]] of [[Emma of Normandy]], who had been given the city as part of her dowry on her marriage to [[\u00c6thelred the Unready]] the previous year.<ref name=\"HOS23\"/>\n\n[[File:Rougemont Castle Gatehouse, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 333534.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The gatehouse of [[Rougemont Castle]]]]\n\nTwo years after the [[Norman Conquest|Norman conquest of England]], Exeter rebelled against [[William the Conquerer|King William]]. [[Gytha Thorkelsd\u00f3ttir]], the mother of the slain [[Harold Godwinson|King Harold]], was living in the city at the time, and William promptly marched west and [[Siege of Exeter (1068)|initiated a siege]]. After 18 days, William accepted the city's honourable surrender, swearing an oath not to harm the city or increase its [[tax|ancient tribute]]. However, William quickly arranged for the building of [[Rougemont Castle]] to strengthen Norman control over the area. Properties owned by Saxon landlords were transferred into Norman hands and, on the death of [[Leofric (bishop)|Bishop Leofric]] in 1072, the Norman [[Osbern FitzOsbern]] was appointed his successor.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 26\u2013}}27.</ref>\n\nIn 1136, early in [[the Anarchy]], Rougemont Castle was held against [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] by [[Baldwin de Redvers]]. Redvers submitted only after a three-month siege, not when the three wells in the castle ran dry, but only after the exhaustion of the large supplies of wine that the garrison was using for drinking, baking, cooking, and putting out fires set by the besiegers.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 31\u2013}}32.</ref> During the siege, King Stephen built an earthen fortification at the site now known (erroneously) as Danes Castle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_places/danes.php|title=Danes Castle|date=4 November 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012|work=Exeter Memories|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914203959/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_places/danes.php|archive-date=14 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Exeter medieval bridge.jpg|thumb|left|Remains of the [[medieval Exe Bridge]], built around 1200<ref>{{cite web|title=The Exe Bridge, Exeter|url=http://www.devon.gov.uk/the-exe-bridge.htm|publisher=Devon County Council|accessdate=30 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208235833/http://www.devon.gov.uk/the-exe-bridge.htm|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>]]\nThe city held a weekly market for the benefit of its citizens from at least 1213, and by 1281 Exeter was the only town in the south-west to have three market days per week. There are also records of seven annual fairs, the earliest of which dates from 1130, and all of which continued until at least the early 16th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/cmh/gaz/devon.html#Exe|title=Online Gazetteer of Markets and Fairs in England & Wales to 1516: Devon|publisher=Centre for Metropolitan History, Institute of Historical Research|accessdate=26 July 2009|last=Letters|first=Samantha|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228181145/http://www.history.ac.uk/cmh/gaz/devon.html#Exe|archive-date=28 December 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the [[Edict of Expulsion|expulsion]] of the Jews of England in 1290, Exeter was home to England's most westerly Jewish community.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Jewish Community of Exeter |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/exeter |publisher=The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot |access-date=2 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702175726/https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/exeter |archive-date=2 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring the high medieval period, both the cathedral clergy and the citizens enjoyed access to sophisticated aqueduct systems which brought pure drinking water into the city from springs in the neighbouring parish of St Sidwell's. For part of their length, these aqueducts were conveyed through a remarkable network of tunnels, or underground passages, which survive largely intact and which may still be visited today.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=Water in the City: The Aqueducts and Underground Passages of Exeter|date=2014|publisher=University of Exeter Press|location=Exeter|isbn=9780859898775|pages=passim}}</ref>\n\nExeter and [[Bristol]] hosted the first recorded Common Council in the Medioeval England.<ref>{{cite book | author = [[James Tait (historian)|James Tait]] | title = The M\u00e9dieval English Borough, Studies on Its Origins and Constitutional History | publisher = [[Manchester University Press]] | year = 1936 | oclc = 1069280340}}. Work cited by {{cite book | author = Richard Holt | author2 = Gervase Rosser | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=gvTgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190 | title = The Medieval Town in England 1200-1540 | page = 190 | language = en | publisher = Routledge | date = June 23, 2014 | isbn = 9781317899815 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511154432/https://books.google.it/books?id=gvTgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&source=bl&ots=1SidsaVI3P&sig=ACfU3U03tfp7By3vbsC1zh0nyXkl6Hna-g&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj27ZjB4JPiAhXJzqQKHShDDesQ6AEwDXoECAcQAQ%23v=onepage&q=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&f=false | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 11 May 2019 }}.</ref> The first detailed and continuous evidence of its existence and activity was founded after 1345<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=i9xRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PR6&lpg=PR6 | title = The Medi\u00e6val Council of Exeter | publisher = Manchester University Press | year = 1931 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511152302/https://books.google.it/books?id=i9xRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PR6&lpg=PR6&dq=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&source=bl&ots=RYkdDacVr_&sig=ACfU3U3E6iYC3jqJVf0NWbYTRStAaj2iZg&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiunaD045PiAhXBsKQKHRw1B-IQ6AEwCXoECAkQAQ%23v=onepage&q=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&f=false | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 11 May 2019 }}</ref> Formed by twelve \"better and more discreet men\" (in [[Latin]]: ''duodecim meliores''), reelected each year, it was originally designed to control the abuse of the Major and of his four [[Steward (office)|stewards]], which presided respectively the borough court and the provost court. The members of the Common Council come from the same elite of wealthy citizens as did the major and the stewards<ref>{{cite book | author = [[Maryanne Kowaleski]] | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=kKbGc-XSsdEC&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101 | title = Local Markets and Regional Trade in Medieval Exeter | page = 101 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | date = Oct 9, 2003 | isbn = 9780521521956 | OCLC = 49594482 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511150744/https://books.google.it/books?id=kKbGc-XSsdEC&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101&dq=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&source=bl&ots=j_zuIrg7hz&sig=ACfU3U0ApfNAPgHuuttef6MR6dnGraO9Yg&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj27ZjB4JPiAhXJzqQKHShDDesQ6AEwDHoECAYQAQ%23v=onepage&q=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&f=false | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 11 May 2019 }}</ref> and this concern introduced a second conflict of interests in the government organism of the city.\n\n===Modern times===\n[[File:Exeter, 1563.jpg|thumb|An illustration of Exeter in 1563, entitled ''Civitas Exoniae (vulgo Excester) urbs primaria in comitatu Devoniae'']]\n; Tudor and Stuart eras\nIn 1537, the city was made a [[county corporate]]. In 1549, the city successfully withstood a month-long siege by the so-called [[Prayer Book Rebellion|Prayer Book rebels]]: Devon and Cornish folk who had been infuriated by the radical religious policies of King Edward VI. The insurgents occupied the suburbs of Exeter, burnt down two of the city gates and attempted to undermine the city walls, but were eventually forced to abandon the siege after they had been worsted in a series of bloody battles with the king's army. A number of rebels were executed in the immediate aftermath of the siege.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=Circled with Stone: Exeter's City Walls, 1485-1660|date=2003|publisher=University of Exeter Press|location=Exeter|isbn=9780859897273|pages=78\u201380, 190\u201391}}</ref> The [[Livery Dole]] [[almshouse]]s and chapel at [[Heavitree]] were founded in March 1591 and finished in 1594.\n\nWhen [[John Hooker (English constitutionalist)|John Hooker]] was appointed to the city payroll in 1561, he created the Court of Orphans as a municipal government for families broken by the premature death of their major economic source. He also was made the Common Council as the legal owner of any estate left to the orphan children of Exeter, until they have reached the age of 21 to be partially paid back.<ref>{{cite web | author = Robert Turner | url = http://www.creditoncourier.co.uk/article.cfm?id=135509&headline=Thorverton%20Society%20members%20heard%20about%20Exeter\u2019s%20fascinating%20history&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 | title = Thorverton Society members heard about Exeter's fascinating history | date = Dec 16, 2018 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511133611/http://www.creditoncourier.co.uk/article.cfm?id=135509&headline=Thorverton%20Society%20members%20heard%20about%20Exeter%E2%80%99s%20fascinating%20history&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 14 August 2019 }}</ref> The orphan tax was used to fund the construction of the Exeter canal.<ref>{{cite publication| author = Charles Carlton | title = John Hooker and Exeter's Court of Orphans | language = en | journal = Huntington Library Quarterly | volume= 36 | issue = 4  | date = August 1973 | pages = 307-316 | jstor=816690 | publisher = University of Pennsylvania Press}}</ref>\n\nThe city's motto, ''[[Semper fidelis]]'', is traditionally held to have been suggested by [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]], in acknowledgement of the city's contribution of ships to help defeat the [[Spanish Armada]] in 1588;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3469|work=Exeter City Council website|title=Exeter's Coat of Arms|accessdate=13 July 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213165222/http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3469|archivedate=13 February 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> however its first documented use is in 1660. Schools in Exeter teach that the motto was bestowed by Charles II in 1660 at the Restoration due to Exeter's role in the [[English Civil War]].\n\nWhen in 1638 Reverend John Wheelwright was exiled from the [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]] and subsequently established a community on the banks of the [[Squamscott River]], he named the region [[Exeter, New Hampshire|Exeter]] after its Devonian counterpart. During the [[American Revolutionary War|American Revolution]] it became the capital of [[New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independencemuseum.org/aim_exeter.htm|title=Exeter - Its History|publisher=American Independence Museum|accessdate=March 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309095405/http://www.independencemuseum.org/aim_exeter.htm|archive-date=9 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nExeter was secured for Parliament at the beginning of the English Civil War, and its defences very much strengthened, but in September 1643 it was captured by the Cornish Royalist Army led by Prince Maurice. Thereafter, the city remained firmly under the king's control until near the end of the war, being one of the final Royalist cities to fall into Parliamentarian hands.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=From Deliverance to Destruction: Rebellion and Civil War in an English City|date=1996|publisher=University of Exeter Press|location=Exeter|isbn=9780859894784|pages=62\u2013108}}</ref> The surrender of Exeter was negotiated in April 1646 at [[Poltimore House]] by [[Thomas Fairfax]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Devon|first=W.G.|last=Hoskins|authorlink=William George Hoskins|year=2003|publisher=Phillimore and Co.|pages=196\u2013198|isbn=978-1-86077-270-2}}</ref> During this period, Exeter was an economically powerful city, with a strong trade of [[wool]]. This was partly due to the surrounding area which was \"more fertile and better inhabited than that passed over the preceding day\" according to Count [[Lorenzo Magalotti]] who visited the city when he was 26 years old.<ref>Gray 2000, p.16</ref> Magalotti writes of over thirty thousand people being employed in the county of Devon as part of the wool and cloth industries, merchandise that was sold to \"the West Indies, Spain, France and Italy\".<ref>Gray 2000, p.18</ref> Celia Fiennes also visited Exeter during this period, in the early 1700s. She remarked on the \"vast trade\" and \"incredible quantity\" in Exeter, recording that \"it turns the most money in a week of anything in England\", between \u00a310,000 and \u00a315,000.<ref>Gray 2000, p.31</ref>\n\n; Georgian and Victorian eras\n[[File:Roque's Map of Exeter 1744.jpg|thumb|right|[[John Rocque]]'s 1744 map of Exeter]]\nEarly in the [[Industrial Revolution]], Exeter's industry developed on the basis of locally available agricultural products and, since the city's location on a fast-flowing river gave it ready access to [[water power]], an early industrial site developed on drained marshland to the west of the city, at [[Exe Island]]. However, when [[steam power]] replaced water in the 19th century, Exeter was too far from sources of coal (or iron) to develop further. As a result, the city declined in relative importance and was spared the rapid 19th-century development that changed many historic European cities. Extensive canal redevelopments during this period further expanded Exeter's economy, with \"vessels of 15 to 16 tons burthen [bringing] up goods and merchandise from [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]] to the City [[Exeter Quay|Quay]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=George|authorlink=George Oliver (historian)|title=History of the City of Exeter|year=1861|page=107|isbn=0-217-79997-3}}</ref> In 1778 a new bridge across the Exe was opened to replace the old medieval bridge. Built at a cost of \u00a330,000, it had three arches and was built of stone.<ref name=\"exebridges\"/>\n\n[[File:Thomas-Shapter-HistoryOfCholeraInExeter1832-map.jpg|thumb|left|Frontispiece to Shapter's \"History of the Cholera in Exeter in 1832\"]]\nIn 1832, [[cholera]], which had been erupting all across Europe, reached Exeter. The only known documentation of this event was written by Dr [[Thomas Shapter]], one of the medical doctors present during the epidemic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapter|first=Thomas|title=The History of the Cholera in Exeter 1832 |year=1848|isbn=0-85409-674-4}}</ref>\n\nThe first railway to arrive in Exeter was the [[Bristol and Exeter Railway]] that opened a station at [[Exeter St Davids railway station|St Davids]] on the western edge in 1844. The [[South Devon Railway Company]] extended the line westwards to [[Plymouth]], opening their own smaller station at [[Exeter St Thomas railway station|St Thomas]], above Cowick Street. A more central railway station, that at [[Exeter Central railway station|Queen Street]], was opened by the [[London and South Western Railway]] in 1860 when it opened its alternative route to London. Butchers [[Lloyd Maunder]] moved to their present base in 1915, to gain better access to the [[Great Western Railway]] for transportation of [[meat processing|meat products]] to London.\n\n[[File:High Street, Exeter, England, ca. 1895.jpg|thumb|right|The High Street ca. 1895]]\nThe first electricity in Exeter was provided by the Exeter Electric Light Company, which was formed at the end of the 1880s, but it was [[Municipalization|municipalised]] in 1896 and became the City of Exeter Electricity Company.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|page=27}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Exeter tram system|horse-drawn trams in Exeter]] were introduced in 1882 with 3 lines radiating from the city's East Gate. One line went to St David's station via New North Road, the Obelisk (where the Clock Tower now stands) and St David's Hill. The second line went out along Heavitree Road to Livery Dole and the third went to Mount Pleasant along Sidwell Street. There was a depot off New North Road.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Lamp standard and ferry, Exeter Quay - geograph.org.uk - 836757.jpg|thumb|left|Lamp standard from the 1905 Exe bridge, installed at [[Butts Ferry]] on [[Exeter Quayside]] in 1983]]\nOn 29 March 1905, a new bridge across the Exe was opened replacing the former Georgian bridge. Made of [[cast-iron]] and steel with a [[Truss arch bridge|three hinged arch]] design, it cost \u00a325,000 and was designed by [[John Wolfe-Barry|Sir John Wolfe Barry]].<ref name=\"exebridges\">{{cite web |url = http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exebridge.php |title = History of the Exe Bridges |work = Exeter Memories |accessdate = 15 September 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120723104916/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exebridge.php |archive-date = 23 July 2012 |url-status = live }}</ref> Also in 1905 [[Exeter Corporation Tramways|electric trams]] replaced the horse trams<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|page=30}}</ref> with a new route which passed along the High Street, down Fore Street and over the new Exe Bridge. Once over the Exe the line divided, with one route along Alphington Road and another along Cowick Street. The line to St David's Station travelled along Queen Street instead of along New North Road and the line to Heavitree was extended.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=86\u201389}}</ref> On 17 March 1917, a tram went out of control going down Fore Street, hit a horse-drawn wagon, then overturned on Exe Bridge and one female passenger was killed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=76\u201378}}</ref> By the 1920s, there were problems with congestion caused by the trams, a need for expensive track renewal work and the slow speed of the trams in Exeter's narrow streets. After much discussion, the council decided to replace the tram service with double-decker buses and the last tram ran on 19 August 1931. The only remaining Exeter tram in service is car 19, now at the [[Seaton Tramway]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=104\u2013124}}</ref>\n\nExeter was bombed by the German Luftwaffe in the Second World War when a total of 18 raids between 1940 and 1942 flattened much of the city centre. \nBetween April 1941 and April 1943 Exeter was defended from enemy bombers by the Polish 307 Squadron, night-fighters nicknamed the 'Lw\u00f3w Eagle Owls' who were based at Exeter Airport. \nThe city of Lw\u00f3w shared the same motto as the city of Exeter - 'Semper Fidelis' (Always faithful).\n\nIn April and May 1942, as part of the Baedeker Blitz and specifically in response to the RAF bombing of L\u00fcbeck and Rostock, 40 acres (16 ha) of the city, particularly adjacent to its central High Street and Sidwell Street, were levelled by incendiary bombing. Many historic buildings in the heart of the city were destroyed and others, including the Cathedral, were damaged. On the night of 4 May, the only hope that Exeter had to avoid total destruction was the heavily outnumbered Polish 307 Squadron which had four available aircraft against the forty German Junkers-88 bombers. During the next 75 minutes, the squadron prevented four German bombers releasing their load of bombs on Exeter. The squadron suffered no casualties in the process. \n156 people were killed in the attacks,[51]however a lot more people in Exeter would have been killed, and the effect on the city much greater had it not been for the \u2018Lw\u00f3w Eagle Owls\u2019.\n\nTo demonstrate British-Polish cooperation and the friendship that had formed between 307 Squadron and Exeter, the squadron presented the city with a Polish flag on 15 November 1942 (the first British city to have had that honour) outside Exeter Cathedral.\n\nSince 2012 a Polish flag is raised over the city's Guildhall on 15 November in honour of 307 Squadron, the day is now known as '307 Squadron Day' in Exeter.\nOn 15 November 2017, a plaque in memory of the squadron was unveiled in the St James Chapel of Exeter Cathedral by the Polish Ambassador His Excellency Arkady Rzegocki.\n\nLarge areas of the city centre were rebuilt in the 1950s when little attempt was made to preserve Exeter's heritage. Damaged buildings were generally demolished rather than restored, and the street plan was altered in an attempt to improve traffic circulation. Former landmarks such as St. Lawrence, the College of the Vicars Choral & Bedford circus disappeared. The modern architecture stands in sharp contrast to the red sandstone of buildings that survived the Blitz.<ref name=payne>{{cite book|title=The West Country: A Cultural History|first=John|last=Payne|p=176|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|year=2011|isbn=978-1-908-49350-7}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Exe Flood Relief Channel - geograph.org.uk - 695255.jpg|thumb|Exe Flood Relief Channel built after the floods of 1960]]\nOn 27 October 1960, following very heavy rain, the Exe overflowed and flooded large areas of Exeter including Exwick, St Thomas and Alphington. The water rose as high as 2 metres above ground level in places and 150 employees of the local firm Beach Bros were trapped for nine hours. 2,500 properties were flooded. Later the same year on 3 December the river levels rose again, flooding 1,200 properties. These floods led to the construction of new [[flood defences]] for Exeter. Work began in 1965, took 12 years to complete and cost \u00a38 million. The defences included three flood relief channels, and were complemented by the construction of two new concrete bridges (built in 1969 and 1972) to replace the old Exe Bridge which had obstructed the flow of the river and made the flooding worse.<ref>{{cite web\n | title        = The Exeter floods of the 1960s\n | url        = http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exeter_floods.php\n | work        = Exeter Memories\n | date        = 28 October 2010\n | accessdate        = 15 September 2012\n | archive-url        = https://web.archive.org/web/20121028034133/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exeter_floods.php\n | archive-date        = 28 October 2012\n | url-status        = live\n }}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nThe [[Princesshay]] shopping centre adjoining the [[Cathedral Close, Exeter|Cathedral Close]] and the High Street was redeveloped between 2005 and 2007,<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Doors open at Princesshay\n |url          = http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/content/articles/2007/09/19/princesshay_opening_day_feature.shtml\n |publisher    = BBC Devon\n |date         = 20 September 2007\n |accessdate   = 21 September 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080217211042/http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/content/articles/2007/09/19/princesshay_opening_day_feature.shtml\n |archive-date = 17 February 2008\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title       = Heaven for shoppers as Princesshay gets off to a flying start with huge crowds for opening day\n | url         = http://www.thisisexeter.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=142326&command=displayContent&sourceNode=142321&contentPK=18452155&folderPk=79876&pNodeId=142331\n | work   = [[Express & Echo]]\n | date        = 21 September 2007\n | accessdate  = 21 September 2007\n}}</ref> despite some local opposition.<ref>{{cite news\n |title        = High Street revamp plans criticised\n |url          = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2817257.stm\n |publisher    = [[BBC News Online]]\n |date         = 4 March 2003\n |accessdate   = 21 September 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20030819112856/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2817257.stm\n |archive-date = 19 August 2003\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref> It incorporates 123 varied residential units.<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Key facts about Princesshay\n |url          = http://www.princesshay.com/community/Keyfacts/index.aspx\n |publisher    = Land Securities Group\n |work         = Princesshay.com\n |accessdate   = 21 September 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071014035943/http://princesshay.com/community/Keyfacts/index.aspx\n |archive-date = 14 October 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nTo enable people with limited mobility to enjoy the city, Exeter Community Transport Association provides manual and powered wheelchairs and scooters (called Shopmobility) for use by anyone suffering from short or long-term mobility impairment to access to the city centre and shopping facilities, events and meetings with friends and company.<ref>{{cite web\n | title       = Shopmobility\n | url       = http://www.exetercta.co.uk/shopmobility.asp\n | work       = Exeter Community Transport Association\n | accessdate       = 13 July 2008\n | archive-url       = https://web.archive.org/web/20120406220728/http://www.exetercta.co.uk/shopmobility.asp\n | archive-date       = 6 April 2012\n | url-status       = dead\n }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008 there was an [[22 May 2008 Exeter bombing|attempted terrorist attack]] on the Giraffe cafe in Princesshay, but the bomber was the only one injured.<ref>{{cite news\n |title        = Nail-bomber given life sentence\n |url          = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7859887.stm\n |publisher    = [[BBC News Online]]\n |date         = 30 January 2009\n |accessdate   = 15 September 2012\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090217020915/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7859887.stm\n |archive-date = 17 February 2009\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref>\n\nA \u00a330 million improvement scheme for the flood defences was approved in March 2015. The plans involve the removal of [[Check dam|check weirs]] and a deeper, \"meandering stream\" in the centre of the drainage channels to improve flow. The plans followed a study by the [[Environment Agency]] that revealed weaknesses in the current defences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exeter-flood-defence-scheme/exeter-flood-defence-scheme|title=Exeter flood defence scheme|access-date=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530163203/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exeter-flood-defence-scheme/exeter-flood-defence-scheme|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[community currency]] for the city, the [[Exeter Pound]], was introduced in 2015<ref>{{cite news|title=Exeter Pound: City launches its own currency|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-34112438|work=BBC News|date=1 September 2015|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717092757/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-34112438|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and dissolved in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-06|title=Home Page - Exeter Pound|url=http://www.exeterpound.org.uk/|website=www.exeterpound.org.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207050042/http://www.exeterpound.org.uk/|archive-date=7 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA serious fire broke out in buildings in central Exeter on 28 October 2016. The fire largely damaged the [[Royal Clarence Hotel]], considered the first venue in England to call itself a hotel. Other historic buildings, including 18 Cathedral Yard and The Well House Tavern,<ref>[http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/historic-building-next-to-destroyed-exeter-hotel-mourns-loss-of-irreplaceable-interior/story-29851231-detail/story.html  \"Architecture experts mourn loss of \"irreplaceable\" interior in building where fire started\", ''Express & Echo'', 29 October 2016] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030150843/http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/historic-building-next-to-destroyed-exeter-hotel-mourns-loss-of-irreplaceable-interior/story-29851231-detail/story.html |date=30 October 2016 }}. Retrieved 29 October 2016</ref> were also severely damaged.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-37796576 Exeter fire wrecks 'oldest hotel in England'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025070740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-37796576 |date=25 October 2018 }} ''[[BBC]]''</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/oct/28/exeter-fire-threatens-royal-clarence-hotel Exeter blaze destroys hotel thought to be oldest in Britain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029113249/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/oct/28/exeter-fire-threatens-royal-clarence-hotel |date=29 October 2016 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> All of the damaged buildings are currently undergoing a major restoration. On 22 February 2017 archaeologists involved in the restoration and repair works of The Royal Clarence Hotel, 18 Cathedral Yard, and The Well House Tavern Pub unearthed medieval pictures, including one of a peacock. The work which had taken three months to complete the process of the deconstruction of the buildings, with every effort being made to save as many historical features as possible. It will take a total of 21 months to restore the fa\u00e7ade external of the buildings and a modern design planned for their interiors of the hotel and 18 Cathedral Yard.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.devonlive.com/royal-clarence-hotel-could-reopen-in-21-months/story-30154366-detail/story.html|title=Royal Clarance Hotel could reopen in 21 months|date=22 February 2017|newspaper=Devon Live|language=en-GB|access-date=30 March 2018}}</ref> On 25 July 2017 the official restoration plans of how the repaired and restored buildings will look once completed, were officially unveiled to the public for the exterior frontal fa\u00e7ade of the buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-40718707|title=Fire-hit 'oldest hotel in England' restoration unveiled|date=25 July 2017|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|language=en-GB|access-date=30 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103232041/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-40718707|archive-date=3 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Further plans were still underway for the interior of the hotel and surrounding buildings the restoration and repair works are being undertaken by construction consultants Thomasons, in partnership with [[Manchester]] architects Buttress, [[Historic England]] and [[Exeter City Council]]. The rebuild was expected to be completed in 18 months with a scheduled reopening of the hotel in 2019. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boutiquehotelier.com/royal-clarence-hotel-reveals-plans-restoration-last-years-fire/|title=The Royal Clarence Hotel reveals plans for restoration after last year\u2019s fire|date=26 July 2017|newspaper=Boutique Hotelier|language=en-GB|access-date=30 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182347/http://www.boutiquehotelier.com/royal-clarence-hotel-reveals-plans-restoration-last-years-fire/|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 November 2019 it was reported that 18 Cathedral Yard had now been repaired having undergone a three-year complete restoration undertaken by the same restorers who restored [[Windsor Castle]] following the [[1992 Windsor Castle fire|1992 fire]] in [[Berkshire]], which was completed in November 1997. There is now a second round of bids for the sale and restoration work to complete the repairs of The Well House Tavern Pub and The Royal Clarence Hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/company-confirms-made-offer-exeter-3514221|title=Company confirms it has made an offer for Exeter Royal Clarence fire site - but doesn\u2019t have hotel plans|date=8 November 2019|newspaper=Devon Live|language=en-GB|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108134713/https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/company-confirms-made-offer-exeter-3514221|archive-date=8 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Exeter Combined Court Centre.jpg|thumb|right|The Exeter Crown and County Courts Building.]]\n[[File:Civic Centre, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 271614.jpg|thumb|upright|Exeter Civic Centre]]\nExeter is in two parliamentary constituencies, the majority of the city is in the [[Exeter (UK Parliament constituency)|Exeter constituency]] but two wards (St Loyes and Topsham) are in [[East Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|East Devon]]. Exeter itself is relatively marginal, and since World War II its Member of Parliament has usually been drawn from the governing party, though the Exeter seat is becoming increasingly a Labour stronghold.  The Exeter MP is [[Ben Bradshaw]] and [[Simon Jupp]] represents East Devon. Exeter is part of the [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England European constituency]], which elects 6 [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s. In 2014, a majority of Exeter voters voted for Labour in the European elections, but in 2019 Labour fell to fourth - the Brexit Party won 28.1% of votes in the city and the Greens won 27.2%.\n\nExeter's [[city council]] is a [[Non-metropolitan district|district]] authority, and shares responsibility for local government with the [[Devon County Council]]. In May 2012 Labour became the majority party on the council. [[Exeter City Council]]'s bid for the city to become a [[Unitary Authority]] was initially approved by ministers in February 2010. A judicial review was called by Devon County Council and the Court held that the Minister had acted unlawfully in granting Unitary status to Exeter at the same time, however, following the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|new coalition government]] announced in May 2010 that the reorganisation would be blocked.<ref name=coalition>{{cite web |url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/documents/digitalasset/dg_187876.pdf |format=PDF |title=The Coalition: our programme for government |publisher=HM Government, United Kingdom |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612015906/http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/%40dg/%40en/documents/digitalasset/dg_187876.pdf |archivedate=12 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/liberaldemocrats/7753762/The-Queens-Speech-Bill-by-Bill.html | title= The Queen's Speech: Bill by Bill | date= 22 May 2010 | accessdate= 24 May 2010 | newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] | first= Patrick | last= Hennessy | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100525102927/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/liberaldemocrats/7753762/The-Queens-Speech-Bill-by-Bill.html | archive-date= 25 May 2010 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nFrom Saxon times, it was in the [[Hundred (county subdivision)|hundred]] of [[Wonford (hundred)|Wonford]].<ref name=\"genuki-devonhundreds\">{{cite web | url=http://genuki.cs.ncl.ac.uk/DEV/Hundreds.html | title=The hundreds of devon | work=GENUKI | accessdate=18 June 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427064112/http://genuki.cs.ncl.ac.uk/DEV/Hundreds.html | archive-date=27 April 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Exeter has had a [[Mayor of Exeter|mayor]] since at least 1207 and until 2002, the city was the oldest 'Right Worshipful' Mayoralty in England. As part of the [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] Exeter was chosen to receive the title of [[Lord Mayor]]. Councillor Granville Baldwin became the first Lord Mayor of Exeter on 1 May 2002 when [[Letters Patent]] were awarded to the city during a visit by the Queen.\nThe Lord Mayor is elected each year from amongst the 39 Exeter city [[councillor]]s and is non-political for the term of office.\n\n===Public services===\nPolicing in Exeter is provided by the [[Devon and Cornwall Constabulary]] who have their headquarters at Middlemoor in the east of the city.\n\nThe [[fire service]] is provided by the [[Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service]], which is headquartered at Clyst St. George near Exeter. It has two fire stations located at Danes Castle and Middlemoor.\n\nThe [[Royal Devon and Exeter NHS Foundation Trust]] has a large hospital located to the south-east of the city centre. Ambulance services in Exeter are provided by [[South Western Ambulance Service]] NHS Trust. The West Trust Divisional HQ and 999 control is in Exeter which provides cover for [[Devon]], Cornwall, [[Somerset]] and the [[Isles of Scilly]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{see also|List of places in Exeter}}\n[[File:River Exe at Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 258229.jpg|thumb|left|The River Exe]]\n\nThe city of Exeter was established on the eastern bank of the [[River Exe]] on a ridge of land backed by a steep hill. It is at this point that the Exe, having just been joined by the [[River Creedy]], opens onto a wide [[flood plain]] and estuary which results in quite common flooding. Historically this was the [[lowest bridging point]] of the River Exe which was tidal and navigable up to the city until the construction of weirs later in its history. This combined with the easily defensible higher ground of the ridge made the current location of the city a natural choice for settlement and trade. In [[George Oliver (historian)|George Oliver]]'s ''The History of the City of Exeter'', it is noted that the most likely reasons for the original settling of what would become modern Exeter was the \"fertility of the surrounding countryside\" and the area's \"beautiful and commanding elevation [and] its rapid and navigable river\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=George|title=History of the City of Exeter|year=1861|page=1|isbn=0-217-79997-3}}</ref>\nIts woodland would also have been ideal for natural resources and hunting.\n\nExeter sits predominantly on sandstone and conglomerate geology, although the structure of the surrounding areas is varied.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/erdp/docs/swchapter/section11/topography.htm|title=Southwest EDRP Geographical Area and Physical Context|last=DEFRA|accessdate=13 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113123623/http://www.defra.gov.uk/erdp/docs/swchapter/section11/topography.htm|archive-date=13 November 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe topography of the ridge which forms the backbone of the city includes a [[volcanic plug]], on which the [[Rougemont Castle]] is situated. The Cathedral is located on the edge of this ridge and is therefore visible for a considerable distance.\n{{Clear}}\n\nExeter is {{convert|80|mile}} west-southwest of [[Salisbury]], {{convert|158|mile}} west-southwest of [[London]], {{convert|18|mile}} north of [[Torquay]], {{convert|36|mile}} northeast of Plymouth and {{convert|74|mile}} east-northeast of [[Truro]].\n\n===Climate===\nExeter has mild wet winters and warm changeable summers with hot and cooler rainy spells. Temperatures do not vary much throughout the year. The hottest month is July with an average high of {{convert|21.7|C|F|}}, and the coldest month is January with an average high of {{convert|8.8|C|F|}}. October is the wettest month with {{convert|88.9|mm|in|}} of rain. Because of shelter from [[Dartmoor]], Exeter is more frost-prone than areas to the southwest, such as [[Plymouth]]. It is also drier, and warmer in the summer for the same reason. The highest recorded temperature in Exeter stands at {{convert|33.5|C|F|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=12&year=1976&indexid=TXx&stationid=2132|title=June 1976|accessdate=5 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311104033/http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=12&year=1976&indexid=TXx&stationid=2132|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> recorded in June 1976, whilst the lowest recorded temperature in Exeter is {{convert|-16.4|C|F|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=18&year=2010&indexid=TNn&stationid=2132|title=December 2010|accessdate=5 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311103528/http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=18&year=2010&indexid=TNn&stationid=2132|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> recorded in December 2010.\n\n{{Exeter weatherbox}}\n\n==Demographics==\nFrom the 2011 Census, the [[Office for National Statistics]] published that Exeter's district area population was 117,773;<ref name=census2011keyfigures>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=62&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374189518359&enc=1|title=Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629193546/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=62&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374189518359&enc=1|archive-date=29 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> 6,697 more people than that of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|last census]] from 2001, which indicated that Exeter had a population of 111,076.<ref name=\"census 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374187787050&enc=1|title=Key Figures for 2001 Census: Key Statistics|accessdate=19 July 2013|work=[[United Kingdom Census 2001|Census 2001]]|publisher=The [[Office for National Statistics]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221162838/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374187787050&enc=1|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time of the 2011 UK census, the ethnic composition of Exeter's population was 93.1% [[White people|White]], with the largest minority ethnic group being [[British Chinese|Chinese]] at 1.7%.<ref name=\"ethnicity\"/> The White British, White Irish and other ethnic group all declined in numbers since the 2001 census (\u22121%, -6% and \u221210% respectively). Meanwhile, the Chinese and ''Other Asian'' had the largest increases (429% and 434% respectively).<ref name=\"ethnicity\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374188868015&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47|title=Ethnic Group, 2001|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|date=9 November 2004|accessdate=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629164315/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374188868015&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47|archive-date=29 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> This excludes the two new ethnic groups added to the 2011 census of Gypsy or Irish Traveller and Arab. Below are the 10 largest immigrant groups in Exeter {{As of|2011|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"ethnicity\"/>\n{|\n! Country of Birth\n! Immigrants in Exeter (2011 Census)\n|-\n|{{flag|China}}\n|1,665\n|-\n|{{flag|Poland}}\n|1,296\n|-\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|710\n|-\n|{{flag|India}}\n|653\n|-\n|{{flag|Ireland}}\n|469\n|-\n|{{flag|South Africa}}\n|438\n|-\n|{{flag|USA}}\n|350\n|-\n|{{flag|France}}\n|310\n|-\n|{{flag|Philippines}}\n|295\n|-\n|{{flag|Australia}}\n|242\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 2011, the City of Exeter had a population of 117,773, while its inner urban subdivision had a population of 113,507. The Exeter USD does not include the outlying suburb of [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]], which while it is administratively part of the city, it is often considered a separate individual settlement as well as the fact its excluded from the city's constituency.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Exeter compared 2011 !! Exeter USD !! Exeter City\n|-\n| White British || 88.1% || 88.3%\n|-\n| Asian || 4.0% || 3.9%\n|-\n| Black || 0.6% || 0.5%\n|}\n\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/ks201ew|title=Official Labour Market Statistics|work=nomisweb.co.uk|access-date=19 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022095240/https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/ks201ew|archive-date=22 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, 11.9% of the population of the Exeter USD (urban subdivision) were non white British, compared with 11.7% for the actual city and surrounding borough of Exeter.\n\nIn 2009, Exeter City was 89.1% [[White British]], compared with 88.3% in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadPage.do?pageId=1001&tc=1462006029195&a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=13&f=27655&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1004x1005&l=1812&o=322&m=0&r=1&s=1462006029195&enc=1|title=Neighbourhood Statistics|date=14 April 2008|work=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk|access-date=30 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120301/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadPage.do?pageId=1001&tc=1462006029195&a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=13&f=27655&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1004x1005&l=1812&o=322&m=0&r=1&s=1462006029195&enc=1|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Exeter Urban Area had a population of 124,079<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/UK-EnglandUA.html?cityid=7160|title=United Kingdom: Urban Areas in England - Population Statistics in Maps and Charts|access-date=1 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413000227/http://www.citypopulation.de/UK-EnglandUA.html?cityid=7160|archive-date=13 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2014, compared with 124,328 for the city and borough of Exeter. While the Exeter Metropolitan Area had a population of 467,257 in the same year and includes Exeter along with [[Teignbridge]], [[Mid Devon]] and [[East Devon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exetercityfutures.com/exeter-travel-work-area/|title=What is the Exeter Travel to Work Area? - Exeter City Futures|date=1 November 2016|access-date=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426031828/https://www.exetercityfutures.com/exeter-travel-work-area/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Out of all the Devon districts, Exeter receives the largest number of commuters from East Devon, followed by Teignbridge. Most of the city's ethnic minority population live in the central, northwestern and eastern suburbs of the city. Outlying areas such as [[Pinhoe]], [[Cowick, Devon|Cowick]] and the expensive suburb of [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]] are all 95% White British as of 2011.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Cathedral from Princesshay 3.JPG|thumb|right|Princesshay Shopping Centre with Exeter Cathedral in the background]]\n[[File:A Middle East Soldier Revisits Britain- Life in Wartime Exeter, Devon, England, UK, October 1943 D16650.jpg|thumb|The Higher Market, Exeter, in 1943; at this time the larger firms such as [[Mac Fisheries]] had joined the smaller shopkeepers' stalls in the market, which, before the war, along with neighbouring Goldsmith Street, was earmarked for demolition; a new Civic Centre was to be built on the site]] \nThe [[Met Office]], the main weather forecasting organisation for the United Kingdom and one of the most significant in the world, relocated from [[Bracknell]] in Berkshire to Exeter in early 2004. It is one of the largest employers in the area (together with the [[University of Exeter]], [[Devon County Council]] and the [[Royal Devon and Exeter NHS Foundation Trust]]).\n\nAround 35,000 people commute into Exeter on a daily basis, from nearby surrounding towns.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1002 | title=Exeter commuters | publisher=Exeter City Council | accessdate=1 June 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807120416/http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1002 | archive-date=7 August 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Exeter provides services, employment and shopping for local residents within the city limits and also from nearby towns in [[Teignbridge]], [[Mid Devon]] and [[East Devon]], together sometimes known as the Exeter & Heart of Devon area (EHOD). Exeter therefore provides for the EHOD area population of 457,400.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.indevon.org.uk/web/uploads/documents/Exeter%20Economic%20Trends%20Feb%2009.pdf | title=EHOD population | publisher=Exeter City Council | accessdate=1 February 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130904173101/http://www.indevon.org.uk/web/uploads/documents/Exeter%20Economic%20Trends%20Feb%2009.pdf | archive-date=4 September 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nExeter has been identified among the top ten most profitable locations for a business to be based.<ref>Dun & Bradstreet, 2001</ref>\n\nThe city centre provides substantial shopping facilities. The High Street is mainly devoted to branches of national chains: a [[New Economics Foundation|NEF]] survey in 2005 rated Exeter as the worst example of a [[clone town]] in the UK, with only a single independent store in the city's High Street, and less diversity (in terms of different categories of shop) than any other town surveyed. In 2010, a similar survey reported the city was still the worst clone town.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/traders-hit-clone-town-attack/story-11755773-detail/story.html|title=Traders hit back after 'clone town' attack|work=Western Morning News|date=15 September 2010|accessdate=15 August 2016}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Three significant shopping areas that connect to the High Street provide a somewhat more varied menu. [[Princesshay]], a [[post-war]] retail area connecting to the south side of the High Street was home to a number of independent stores prior to redevelopment in 2007, but is now also largely occupied by national chains. It is still intended that a number of the new units will be let to local independent stores.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The [[House of Fraser]] building on the high street has been bought buy a local wealth performance management firm, Prydis, who have released their plans to redevelop the building as a 3-storey hotel with a rooftop bar and retail shops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/first-pictures-house-fraser-plans-2743509|title=First pictures of House of Fraser plans show dramatic rooftop bar|last=Smith|first=Colleen|date=2019-04-10|website=devonlive|access-date=2019-11-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411161754/https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/first-pictures-house-fraser-plans-2743509|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the other side of the High Street, the partly undercover Guildhall Shopping Centre houses a mixture of national and more regional shops, and connects to the wholly enclosed Harlequins Centre where smaller businesses predominate. Smaller streets off the High Street such as Gandy Street also offer a range of independent shops.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nOn 26 June 2004, Exeter was granted [[Fairtrade City]] status.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exeter.gov.uk/people-and-communities/communities/fairtrade/|title=Fairtrade - Exeter City Council|website=www.exeter.gov.uk|access-date=2019-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416050343/https://exeter.gov.uk/people-and-communities/communities/fairtrade/|archive-date=16 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Exeter contains a number of tourist attractions, the city is not dominated by tourism, with only 7% of employment dependent on tourism compared with 13% for Devon as a whole (2005 figures).<ref>[http://www.tourisminsights.info/STATISTICS/STAT1.HTML South West Tourism (2006)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420021523/http://www.tourisminsights.info/STATISTICS/STAT1.HTML |date=20 April 2009 }}, ''The Value of Tourism in Devon 2005''. Exeter: SWT</ref>\n\nThere are also plans to build on land in the Teignbridge and East Devon areas, which border Exeter's boundaries, as part of the \"Exeter Growth Point\" strategy, which includes the [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new town]] of [[Cranbrook, Devon|Cranbrook]] located about 5 miles the east of the city in East Devon where construction began in 2011 and is now home to several thousand residents.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/South-West-Exeter/ | title=Exeter Growth Point | date=1 January 2011 | publisher=Devon County Council | accessdate=1 January 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521050555/http://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/South-West-Exeter/ | archive-date=21 May 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastdevon.gov.uk/planning/planning-policy/cranbrook-plan/the-development-of-cranbrook-and-the-cranbrook-plan/|title=Cranbrook Plan|website=East Devon|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426031830/http://www.eastdevon.gov.uk/planning/planning-policy/cranbrook-plan/the-development-of-cranbrook-and-the-cranbrook-plan/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/Cranbrook/|title=Cranbrook - Exeter and East Devon Growth Point|website=www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk|access-date=2019-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426031834/https://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/Cranbrook/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n{{further|Grade I listed buildings in Exeter|Grade II* listed buildings in Exeter}}\n{{wide image|Exeter panorama 1.jpg|900px|A panorama of the city taken from the roof of the north tower of the cathedral}}\nAmong the notable buildings in Exeter are:\n\n===Religious buildings===\n[[File:ExeterCathedral-4.jpg|thumb|[[Exeter Cathedral]] and the [[Devon County War Memorial]]]]\n{{See also|Exeter#Religion}}\n* The [[Exeter Cathedral|cathedral]], founded in 1050 when the bishop's seat was moved from the nearby town of [[Crediton]] (birthplace of [[Saint Boniface]]) because Exeter's Roman walls offered better protection against \"pirates\", presumably [[Viking]]s. A statue of [[Richard Hooker (theologian)|Richard Hooker]], the 16th century [[Anglican]] theologian, who was born in Exeter, has a prominent place in the [[Cathedral Close, Exeter|Cathedral Close]].\n* [[St Nicholas Priory]] in Mint Lane, the remains of a [[monastery]], later used as a private house and now a museum owned by the city council. The priory was founded in 1087 and was home to Benedictine monks for over 400 years, until it was closed and partly demolished by [[Henry VIII]]. The remaining buildings were then sold off in 1602 and became the home of the locally wealthy Hurst family. The property has been fully renovated by Exeter City Council, and the small garden area features Tudor plants and herbs<ref>''St Nicholas Priory: Discover a Tudor Home'' Booklet produced by Exeter City Council (July 2009)</ref>\n* A number of medieval churches including [[St Mary Steps, Exeter|St Mary Steps]] which has an elaborate clock.\n* The [[Exeter Synagogue]] is the third oldest synagogue in Britain, completed in 1763.\n*[[St Thomas' Church, Exeter|St Thomas' Church]], originally built in the 13th century just outside the city walls. Destroyed by fire and rebuilt in the 17th century; grade I listed.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1169954|desc=Church of St Thomas|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Exeter, Kathedrale St. Peter -- 2013 -- 1.jpg|900px|A panorama of Exeter Cathedral and [[Cathedral Close, Exeter|Cathedral Close]]}}\n\n===Secular buildings===\n[[File:The House that Moved in Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 1727313.jpg|thumb|upright|\"The House that Moved\", West Street, Exeter]]\n* The [[ruins]] of [[Rougemont Castle]], built soon after the [[Norman Conquest]]; later parts of the castle were still in use as a County Court until early 2006 when a new [[Crown Court]]s building opened. A plaque near the ruined Norman gatehouse recalls the fate of [[Alice Molland]], tried for [[witchcraft]] at Exeter in 1685, and reputedly the last person in England to have been executed for that crime; others convicted of witchcraft had been hanged in Exeter in 1581, 1610, and 1682.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=It is but an old wytche gonne\u2019: Prosecution and Execution for Witchcraft in Exeter, 1558-1610|journal=History|date=April 2011|volume=96|issue=2|pages=129\u201351}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=James|title=Instruments of Darkness: Witchcraft in England, 1550-1750|date=1996|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|location=London|page=121}}</ref>\n* The [[Exeter Guildhall|Guildhall]], which has medieval foundations and has been claimed to be the oldest municipal building in England still in use.<ref>See for example: {{cite book|last=Hele's School Historical Society. |title=Exeter \u2013 Then and Now|year=1947|publisher=A. Wheaton & Co|page=31}}</ref>\n* Mol's Coffee House, a historic building in the Cathedral Close.\n* Tuckers' Hall, a fine old building that is still used for smart functions.\n* The [[Custom House, Exeter|Custom House]] in the attractive [[Exeter Quay|Quay area]], which is the oldest brick building surviving in the city.\n* \"The House That Moved\", a 14th-century [[Tudor style architecture|Tudor]] building, earned its name in 1961 when it was moved from its original location on the corner of Edmund Street in order for a new road to be built in its place. Weighing more than twenty-one tonnes, it was strapped together and slowly moved a few inches at a time to its present-day position.\n*[[Parliament Street, Exeter|Parliament Street]] in the city centre is one of the narrowest streets in the world.\n*The [[Butts Ferry]], an ancient [[cable ferry]] across the River Exe.\n*[[Wyvern Barracks]], a former artillery barracks, dates back to about 1800.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1109979|desc=Guard House and attached wall Wyvern Barracks|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Higher Barracks, Exeter|Higher Barracks]], a former cavalry barracks, dates back to 1794.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_buildings/higher_barracks.php|title=The Higher Barracks, or Cavalry Barracks - Howell Road|publisher=Exeter memories|accessdate=9 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221084936/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_buildings/higher_barracks.php|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*The [[Devon County War Memorial]] in the Cathedral Close, designed by [[Sir Edwin Lutyens]] and unveiled in 1922 by [[Edward VIII|Edward, Prince of Wales]].<ref>{{National Heritage List for England |num=1393228 |desc=Devon County War Memorial and Processional Way|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany of these are built in the local dark red [[sandstone]], which gives its name to the castle and the park that now surrounds it (Rougemont means red hill). The pavements on Queen Street are composed of the rock [[diorite]] and exhibit [[feldspar]] crystals, while those around Princesshay are composed of [[granodiorite]].\n\n===Northernhay Gardens===\nLocated just outside the castle, [[Northernhay Gardens]] is the oldest public open space in England, being originally laid out in 1612 as a pleasure walk for Exeter residents.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Car===\n[[File:M5 Bridge crosses the River Exe - geograph.org.uk - 1109085.jpg|thumb|Bridge carrying the [[M5 motorway]] across the [[River Exe]]]]\nThe [[M5 motorway]] to [[Bristol]] and Exeter starts at [[Birmingham]], and connects at Bristol with the [[M4 motorway|M4]] to London and [[South Wales]]. The older [[A30 road]] provides a more direct route to London via the [[A303 road|A303]] and [[M3 motorway (Great Britain)|M3]]. The M5 is the modern lowest bridging point of the [[River Exe]]. Going westwards, the [[A38 road|A38]] connects Exeter to [[Plymouth]] and south east [[Cornwall]], whilst the A30 continues via [[Okehampton]] to north and west Cornwall. The cities of [[Bristol]], [[Plymouth]], [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Salisbury]] and [[Truro]] can all be reached within 2 hours.\n\nTravel by car in the city is often difficult with regular jams centred on the Exe Bridges area. Historically, the bridges were a significant bottleneck for holiday traffic heading to southwest England, leading to the construction of the first bypass in the mid-1930s over [[Countess Wear|Countess Wear Bridge]], followed by the M5 in 1977.<ref name=dcc>{{cite web|url=https://www.devonnewscentre.info/the-changing-face-of-bridge-road-in-exeter/|title=The changing face of Bridge Road in Exeter|publisher=Devon County Council|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=15 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012100749/https://www.devonnewscentre.info/the-changing-face-of-bridge-road-in-exeter/|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> To further address the problem of congestion in the city centre, [[Devon County Council]] has current park and ride services and is considering the introduction of [[congestion charge]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/6125042.stm|title=Drivers facing congestion charge|publisher=BBC News|date=7 November 2006|accessdate=13 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216082313/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/6125042.stm|archive-date=16 February 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\n{{refimprove section|date=September 2019}}\n\nExeter's main operator of local buses is [[Stagecoach South West]], which operates most of the services in the city. [[Dartline]] is a minor operator in the City. Former Cooks Coaches were taken over by [[Stagecoach Devon|Stagecoach]] forming Stagecoach South West. [[Western Greyhound]] was also a main operator connecting Exeter to Cornwall, [[Somerset]] and many different places in [[South West England]] until being taken over by [[First South West|First Devon & Cornwall]], [[Plymouth Citybus]] and [[Stagecoach South West]] in March 2015.\n\nThe High Street, pedestrianised except for bus and bicycle traffic, serves as the main hub for local buses. Country and express services operate from the city's bus station, in Paris Street, which intersects the High Street at its eastern end; some also call at [[Exeter St Davids railway station]] for direct connection to train services.\n\nCountry bus services, mostly operated by Stagecoach, run from Exeter to most places in East and [[North Devon]], but some are very infrequent. Regional express services run to [[Plymouth]], [[Torbay]], [[Bude]], and along the [[Jurassic Coast]] to [[Lyme Regis]]. [[National Express Coaches|National Express]] operates long-distance routes, for example to [[London Heathrow Airport|Heathrow]] and London.\n\n===Railway===\n[[File:2008 at Exeter St Davids - station frontage.jpg|thumb|Exeter St Davids Railway Station]]\n\nExeter is considered to be the main rail hub within the south-west and is linked to most branch lines in Devon, including to [[Riviera Line|Paignton]], [[Avocet Line|Exmouth]], [[Tarka Line|Barnstaple]] and [[Okehampton]] (by a special service). This makes it possible to reach most stations in Devon directly from [[Exeter St Davids railway station|Exeter St Davids]], although only during the summer months.\n\nExeter is served by three main railway stations. [[Exeter St Davids railway station|Exeter St Davids]] is served by all services and is a major [[interchange station]] within the [[South West Peninsula]]'s rail network, whilst [[Exeter Central railway station|Exeter Central]] is more convenient for the city centre but served only by local services and the main line route to London Waterloo. In the south-west of the city, [[Exeter St Thomas railway station|Exeter St Thomas]] serves the western side of the city. There are also six suburban stations, [[Topsham railway station|Topsham]], [[St James Park railway station|St James Park]], [[Polsloe Bridge railway station|Polsloe Bridge]], [[Pinhoe railway station|Pinhoe]], [[Digby and Sowton railway station|Digby & Sowton]] and [[Newcourt (Exeter) railway station|Newcourt]], served only by local services.\n\nThere are two main line railway routes from Exeter to London, the faster [[Reading to Taunton line|route via Taunton and Reading to London Paddington]] and the slower [[West of England Main Line]] via [[Salisbury, England|Salisbury]] and [[Basingstoke]] to [[London Waterloo railway station|London Waterloo]]. Another main line, the [[Cross Country Route]], links Exeter with [[Bristol]], [[Birmingham]], [[Derby]], [[Leeds]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[Edinburgh]] and [[Aberdeen]]. [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]] and [[CrossCountry]] services continue westwards along the [[Exeter to Plymouth Line]], variously serving [[Torquay]], [[Plymouth]] and [[Cornwall]]. Local branch lines run to [[Paignton]] (see [[Riviera Line]]), [[Exmouth, Devon|Exmouth]] (see [[Avocet Line]]) and [[Barnstaple]] (see [[Tarka Line]]). There is also a summer weekend service to [[Okehampton]] for access to [[Dartmoor]].\n\nThe [[Exeter to Plymouth railway of the LSWR|Exeter to Plymouth line of the London and South Western Railway (LSWR)]] used to provide an alternative route via [[Okehampton]] connecting north [[Cornwall]] and [[Plymouth]] to Exeter and the rest of the UK railway system until its closure in 1968. There are proposals to reopen the line from Okehampton, Tavistock to Bere Alston for a through service to Plymouth.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Harris| first = Nigel| title = Taking trains back to Tavistock| journal = Rail| issue = 590| pages = 40\u201345| publisher = Bauer| year = 2008}}</ref> On the night of 4 February 2014, amid high winds and extremely rough seas, part of the [[South Devon Railway sea wall]] at Dawlish was breached, washing away around {{convert|40|m}} of the wall and the ballast under the railway immediately behind and closing the [[Exeter to Plymouth Line]]. [[Network Rail]] began repair work<ref>{{cite web|title=UK storms destroy railway line and leave thousands without power|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26042990|publisher=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=5 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205072449/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26042990|archive-date=5 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and the line reopened on 4 April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dawlish's storm-damaged railway line reopens|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-devon-26874503|accessdate=4 April 2014|work=BBC news|date=4 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404063923/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-devon-26874503|archive-date=4 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In the wake of widespread disruption caused by damage to the mainline track at [[Dawlish]] by coastal storms in February 2014, [[Network Rail]] are considering reopening the Bere Alston to Okehampton and Exeter section of the [[Exeter to Plymouth railway of the LSWR|former LSWR line]] as an alternative to the coastal route.<ref>{{cite web | title=Network Rail chooses Dawlish alternative route | publisher=BBC News | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26110559 | date=10 February 2014 | accessdate=10 February 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140211080406/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26110559 | archive-date=11 February 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Air===\n[[File:ExeterAirportUK.jpg|thumb|Exeter International Airport]]\n[[Exeter Airport]] lies east of the city, and the local airline, previously called [[Jersey European]] and [[British European]] but now known as [[Flybe]], is a significant local employer. It is also a base for [[Thomson Airways]] with flights to [[Faro Airport|Faro]], [[Mallorca]], [[Lanzarote]] and elsewhere. The airport offers a range of scheduled flights to British and Irish regional airports and [[Charter airline|charter]] flights. Connections to international hubs began with [[Paris-Charles de Gaulle]] in 2005 and later a daily service to [[Amsterdam Schiphol Airport]]. [[Ryanair]] started flights in 2019 to Luqa, Naples and Malaga.\n\n===Canal===\n[[File:Exeter Canal Basin - geograph.org.uk - 238695.jpg|thumb|Exeter Canal Basin]]\nThe [[Exeter Canal]], also known as the Exeter Ship Canal, was first constructed by John Trew in about 1566,<ref>{{cite book|first=Kenneth R.|last=Clew|title=The Exeter Canal|location=Chichester|publisher=Phillimore|year=1984|isbn=0-85033-544-2}}</ref> representing one of the oldest artificial waterways in Britain. It was cut to bypass the St James' Weir that had been built across the [[River Exe]] at Duckes Marsh to provide a leat to a mill constructed just below the confluence of the Northbrook, in what became the village of Countess Weir. The weir had the effect of preventing water-born trade in the City of Exeter and forced boats to load and unload at [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]] from where the [[Earl of Devon|Earls of Devon]] were able to exact large tolls to transport goods to and from Exeter.\n\nOriginally 3 feet deep and 16 feet wide (0.9 m by 5 m), the canal ran {{convert|2.0|mi|2|abbr=out}} from the confluence of the Matford Brook, just above Bridge Road in [[Countess Wear|Countess Weir]] to Haven Banks, close to the centre of Exeter. In order to maintain a consistent navigable water level, another weir was constructed by Trew, just below the point the canal joins the river. The canal was later extended south to Topsham Lock {{convert|3.65|mi|2|abbr=out}}, deepened and widened, and later still it was extended to Turf Lock near [[Manor_of_Powderham|Powderham]] {{convert|5.0|mi|2|abbr=out}}. The canal was successful until the middle of the 19th century since when its use gradually declined \u2013 the last commercial use was in 1972. However it is now widely used for leisure purposes, and the city basin is part of a \u00a324&nbsp;million redevelopment scheme.\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of schools in Devon}}\n[[File:Laver Building, University of Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 148746.jpg|thumb|upright|Laver Building, University of Exeter]]\nThe [[University of Exeter]] has two campuses in the city, both notable for their attractive parkland.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} It is one of the largest employers in the city. The university includes the [[University of Exeter Business School|Business School]], the [[Bill Douglas Cinema Museum]], the [[Henry Wellcome]] building for Biocatalysis, and, as of September 2018, the Exeter Centre for [[Ellen MacArthur Foundation|Circular Economy]].\n\n[[Exeter College, Exeter|Exeter College]] is a [[further education]] college. It previously operated as the sole [[sixth form]] for the entire [[maintained school]] sector in the city. However, in 2014 [[Exeter Mathematics School]] was established, a [[Free school (England)|free school]] sixth form with a specialism in Mathematics.\n\nFor about 30 years the city of Exeter operated a [[maintained school]] system in which the divisions between phases came at different ages from most of the United Kingdom, with first, middle and high rather than infant, junior and secondary schools, so that children transferred between schools at the age of about 8 and 12 rather than 7 and 11.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} From 2005, however, it has adopted the more usual pattern, because of the pressures of the UK [[National Curriculum (England, Wales and Northern Ireland)|National Curriculum]]. The changeover back to the more typical structure led to a citywide, [[Private Finance Initiative|PFI]] funded, rebuilding programme for the high schools and led to the changing of names for some schools. Following the reorganisation there are 25 primary schools, four referral schools, three [[special school]]s and five secondary schools within Exeter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devon.gov.uk/index/learning/schools/locations_and_details.htm|title=Schools, locations and details|work=Devon County Council website|accessdate=19 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704151841/http://www.devon.gov.uk/index/learning/schools/locations_and_details.htm|archive-date=4 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The secondary schools are [[Isca Academy]] (formerly Priory High School), [[St James School, Exeter|St James School]] (formerly St James High School), [[St Luke's Science and Sports College]] (formerly Vincent Thompson High School), [[St Peter's Church of England Aided School]] (a consolidation of the former Bishop Blackall High School for Girls and Heles High School for Boys), and [[West Exe School]] (formerly St Thomas High School).\n\nThe city has a number of independent schools, including [[Exeter School]], [[Exeter Cathedral School]], [[The Maynard School]], [[Bramdean School]], [[St Wilfrid's School, Exeter|St Wilfrid's School]] and [[Exeter Tutorial College]].\n\nThere are specialist schools for pupils with sensory needs, including Exeter Royal Academy for Deaf Education, and the West of England School for the Partially Sighted.\n\nThe Atkinson Unit is a secure specialist residential and educational complex for children in care or [[Detention of suspects|remanded]] by the courts.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Michael's church, and Episcopal building, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 287157.jpg|thumb|upright|St. Michael's Church and Episcopal Building]]\nNumerous churches, and other religious buildings, are present in Exeter. Of which a majority belong to differing Christian denominations, with the exception of an [[Church of England]] cathedral. The medieval city of Exeter had nearly 70 churches, chapels, monasteries and almshouses.<ref>Nicholas Orme ''The Churches of Medieval Exeter''. Exeter: Impress Books, 2014; back cover</ref>\n\n[[Exeter Cathedral]] is the seat of the [[Bishop of Exeter]]. The erection of the present building was completed in approximately 1400, and possesses the longest uninterrupted vaulted ceiling in England, as well as other noticeable characteristics. A collective of Anglican churches form the [[Deanery of Christianity (Exeter)|Exeter Deanery]].\n\nOn the other hand, the Catholic community of Exeter occupy two Churches, the [[Sacred Heart Church, Exeter|Sacred Heart]] and the [[Blessed Sacrament Church, Exeter|Blessed Sacrament]], with congregations reflecting the nature of older and more recent immigration.\n\n[[Exeter Synagogue]], located within a near proximity to Mary Arches Street, was completely erected in 1763.\n\nExeter's mosque and Islamic centre are located on York Road. The first mosque was opened in 1977.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tellingourstoriesexeter.org.uk/index.php?mact=News,cntnt01,detail,0&cntnt01articleid=18&cntnt01origid=57&cntnt01returnid=80|title=Telling our stories, finding our roots Exeter Multicultural History - Timeline|website=www.tellingourstoriesexeter.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> The purpose-built mosque opened in 2011.\n\nAt the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]], 69.12% of Exeter's population stated their religion as Christian, which is mildly lower than the regional average of 73.99% and the national average of 71.74%. Despite this, all other religions had exceeded the regional average at just under 1%. Although, they were much lower than the national average with the exemption of Buddhism. 20.45% of Exeter's population stated they had no religion, which was higher than the regional average of 16.75% and the national average of 14.59%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=276927&c=Exeter&d=13&e=15&g=436252&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1231680745917&enc=1&dsFamilyId=17|title=Religion|date=1 April 2001|work=[[United Kingdom Census 2001]]|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=11 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613050407/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=276927&c=Exeter&d=13&e=15&g=436252&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1231680745917&enc=1&dsFamilyId=17|archive-date=13 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anglican churches===\n[[File:St David's church, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 213553.jpg|thumb|St. David's Church, Exeter]]\n[[John Betjeman]] (writing in 1958) selects [[St David's Church, Exeter|St David's]] (\"[[W. D. Caroe|Caroe]]'s best church\"), [[St Martin's Church, Exeter|St Martin's]] (\"characteristic little city church, 15th century\"), [[Church of St Mary Steps,  Exeter|St Mary Steps]] (\"medieval city church; font\"), St Michael's (\"Victorian, on a fine site\"), and [[St Thomas' Church, Exeter|St Thomas's]] (\"fittings\"). His coverage of St Mary Arches is more detailed: \"worth seeing ... as the completest Norman church in Devon: beautifully light and airy after its restoration from the bombing in 1942. 18th-century altar arrangements. Memorials to Exeter worthies, 16th to 18th centuries.\"<ref>Betjeman, John, ed. (1968) ''Collins Pocket Guide to English Parish Churches; the South''. London: Collins; p. 164</ref>\n\nThe aforementioned collective of Anglican churches include St David's Church, located near to St. David's Station. The church was envisaged by [[W. D. Caroe]], with the windows being manufactured by Kempe & Tower, and was later constructed between 1897 and 1900. A tower stands on the northeast side, with the overall design being described as \u201chighly picturesque by Nikolaus Pevsner.\n\nSt Edmund-on-the-Bridge was built on the Exe Bridge ca. 1230\u201340. Two arches of the bridge remain under the undercroft though the church was rebuilt in the Perpendicular style in 1835, using the old materials.\n\nSt Martin's is in the [[Cathedral Close]]; the plan is odd, and there are numerous items of church furniture, though these are not of high aesthetic value. St Mary Arches is a Norman church with aisles. St Mary Steps was originally by the West Gate of the city; the font is Norman, and there is a remarkable early clock. St Michael, Heavitree was built in 1844\u201346 and extended later in the century. [[St Pancras Church, Exeter|St Pancras]] is of the 13th century and has a nave and chancel only; the font is Norman. The plan of [[St Petrocks Church, Exeter|St Petroc's]] church is highly unusual: a second chancel has been added facing north while the original chancel has another use and faces east. There are two aisles on the south, one of 1413 and another of the 16th century.\n\nSt Sidwell's church is by W. Burgess, 1812, in the Perpendicular style. [[St Stephens Church, Exeter|St Stephen's church]] is partly of the 13th century but most of the structure is as rebuilt in 1826.<ref>Pevsner, N. (1952) ''South Devon''. Harmondsworth: Penguin Books; pp. 148\u201353</ref> [[St Michael and All Angels Church, Exeter|St Michael and All Angels Church]] on Mount Dinham has a spire which exceeds the height of the towers of Exeter Cathedral.\n\n==Sport==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:St James Park Exeter City.jpg|thumb|[[St James Park (Exeter)|St James Park]], the home of [[Exeter City F.C.]]]] -->\n\n===Rugby Union===\n\nThe [[rugby union]] team [[Exeter Chiefs]] play their home games at [[Sandy Park]] stadium, located adjacent to junction 30 of the M5, and frequently achieve attendances of over 11,000 spectators. Sandy Park was constructed in September 2006 and cost \u00a315 million. Exeter Chiefs relocated there from their previous stadium at the County Ground which had been used continually from 1905.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Exeter Chiefs \u2013 History|url=http://www.exeterchiefs.co.uk/club-info/history/|accessdate=9 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307010105/http://www.exeterchiefs.co.uk/club-info/history/|archive-date=7 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nExeter Chiefs achieved promotion in the [[2009\u201310 RFU Championship|2009\u201310 season]] following concessive victories against [[Bristol Rugby|Bristol]] and have since remained within the highest division of English rugby, the [[Aviva Premiership]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn the [[2011\u201312 Aviva Premiership|2011\u201312 season]] of the Aviva Premiership, Exeter Chiefs  finished in fifth place, earning a spot in the [[Heineken Cup]]. Exeter Chiefs won their first piece of silverware when they defeated Northampton 15\u20138 at Sandy Park in the 2014 LV Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/26551754 |title=Cup final: Exeter Chiefs 15-8 Northampton Saints |last=Osborne |first=Chris |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=16 March 2014 |access-date=13 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901102155/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/26551754 |archive-date=1 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Furthermore, Exeter Chiefs were crowned English champions in 2017, after defeating Wasps RFC in the Aviva Premiership final at Twickenham.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/40018239 |title=Premiership final: Wasps 20-23 Exeter Chiefs (aet) |last=Law |first=James |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=27 May 2017 |access-date=13 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829132950/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/40018239 |archive-date=29 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The city also has two other clubs: Wessex Rugby Club, which is located in Exwick, and Exeter Saracens Rugby Club,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exetersaracens.co.uk/|title=Exeter Saracens Rugby Football Club Website|accessdate=19 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726193243/http://www.exetersaracens.co.uk/|archive-date=26 July 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> which is located in Whipton.\n\n===Football===\n\n[[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] is Exeter's predominant Professional Association football club. They play their home games at St James Park, where they have remained since they were established in 1904. Originally, St James Park was a field used for fattening pigs. A redevelopment scheme was introduced in 2017, due to finish the year after, apparently providing a vastly increased fan experience.\n\nExeter City F.C became founder members of the [[Football League]]'s new [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] (south) in 1920, but have never progressed beyond the third tier of the English football league system. In 2003, Exeter City F.C were relegated to the [[Football Conference|Conference]] before reclaiming their Football League place in 2008 and achieving successive promotions to [[Football League One|League One]] in 2009. However, Exeter City F.C were relegated to League Two at the end of the 2011/12 season.\n\n===Cricket===\n\nExeter Cricket Club administer three teams that play in the Devon Cricket League. The first of which plays in the Premier Division at first XI level and the next plays at second XI level.\n\nExeter Cricket Club play their home games at Country Ground where they have remained for a period exceeding 180 years.\n\n===Rowing===\n\nExeter [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]] Club enjoys success both locally and nationally, and has a recorded history originating in the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeterrowingclub.com/general/history.php|title=History \u2013 Exeter Rowing Club|accessdate=15 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925235856/http://www.exeterrowingclub.com/general/history.php|archive-date=25 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Exeter Rowing Regatta is run annually in July, and is the eldest and largest regatta in the South West, with racing first recorded on the river in the 1860s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter-regatta.co.uk|title=About the regatta|accessdate=15 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819151025/http://www.exeter-regatta.co.uk/|archive-date=19 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Squash===\n\nThe Devon & Exeter [[Squash (sport)|Squash]] club is one of the most active squash clubs in the region, annually hosting the Exeter Diamonds.\n\n===Speedway===\n\nExeter's [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] team, [[Exeter Falcons]], was established in 1929 and were located at the County Ground until its permanent closure in 2005.\n\nIn a fixture during the 2004 season, they defeated [[Rye House Cobras|Rye House]] by the maximum score of 75\u201315.\n\nAt the site, Exeter Falcons member Jack Geran trained younger members in the art of the shale sport on a speedway training track in the late 1970s and early-1980s. Speedway was also staged briefly at tracks in [[Alphington, Devon|Alphington]] and Peamore after the Second World War.\n\nThe history of [[Motorcycle speedway|Speedway]] in Exeter up to the mid-1950s has been recorded in three books by Tony Lethbridge.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Literature===\n[[File:Riddle-pyramid-comp.jpeg|thumb|upright|The Exeter Riddle Sculpture in Exeter High Street, created by artist Michael Fairfax and installed in 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml|title=BBC - Devon Features|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2018-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504020912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml|archive-date=4 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\nThe ''[[Exeter Book]]'', an anthology of Anglo Saxon poetry, is conserved in the vaults of Exeter Cathedral. The Exeter Book originates from the 10th century and is one of four manuscripts that between them encompass all surviving poetry composed in [[Old English language|Old English]]. Predominantly, the Book incorporates shorter poems, several religious pieces, and a series of [[riddle]]s, a handful of which are famously [[lewd]]. A selection of the aforementioned riddles are inscribed on a highly polished steel obelisk situated in High Street, placed there on 30 March 2005.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml The Riddle of the new Exeter Statue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504020912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml |date=4 May 2008 }} (retrieved 19 November 2010)</ref>\n\nAnother famous piece of literature is the ''[[Exeter Domesday|Exon Domesday]]'', a composite land and tax register of 1086. The piece contains a variety of administrative materials concerning the counties of Cornwall, Devon, Dorset, Somerset and Wiltshire. This piece is also conserved in Exeter Cathedral.\n\nIn 2019, the city became a [[UNESCO]] [[City of Literature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.exeter.gov.uk/exeter-only-uk-city-to-be-awarded-unesco-city-of-literature-status/|title=Exeter becomes City of Literature|access-date=31 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031182330/https://news.exeter.gov.uk/exeter-only-uk-city-to-be-awarded-unesco-city-of-literature-status/|archive-date=31 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nNumerous theatres occupy Exeter. One of which is the [[Northcott Theatre]]. The Northcott Theatre is situated in the Streatham campus of the University of Exeter and is one of relatively few provincial English theatres to maintain its own [[repertory|repertory company]]. This theatre is the successor to the former [[Theatre Royal, Exeter]] which was permanently closed in 1962.\n\n[[File:Barnfield Theatre (geograph 4203993).jpg|thumb|left|Barnfield Theatre]]\nAnother popular theatre in Exeter is the [[Barnfield Theatre]]. Originally, the building was constructed as Barnfield Hall by Exeter Literary Society towards the end of the 19th century and converted in 1972. Currently, the theatre is a charity and is used as a venue for amateur and professional theatrical companies.\n\nThe Cygnet Theatre in Friars Walk is the home of the [[Cygnet Training Theatre]] and is a member of the [[Conference of Drama Schools]]. As well as performances given by students in training, this theatre also stages performances from visiting repertory companies and has a good reputation for quality events.\n\nThe Bike Shed Theatre and Cocktail Bar opened in September 2010 before permanently closing in March 2018. The Theatre was forced to close after failing to generate enough profit from the cocktail bar in order to operate the theatre. Fundamentally, the theatre offered intimate live music and performances and operated from basement premises in Fore Street.\n\nAdditionally, more innovative and contemporary performances, theatrical productions and dance pieces are programmed by Exeter Phoenix in Exeter City Centre and The Exeter Corn Exchange in Market Street.\n\n===Music===\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2010}}\nThere are two festivals each year, of all the arts but with a particular concentration of musical events: the annual \"Vibraphonic\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibraphonic2011.co.uk/|title=Vibraphonic 2011 website|work=Vibraphonic 2011 Festival website|access-date=5 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929144320/http://www.vibraphonic2011.co.uk/|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> festival, held in March provides a fortnight of soul, blues, jazz, funk, reggae and electronic music.\n\nThe largest orchestra based in Exeter is the EMG Symphony Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emgsymphonyorchestra.org|title=EMG Symphony Orchestra website|accessdate=19 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509124758/http://www.emgsymphonyorchestra.org/|archive-date=9 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> which frequently presents concerts at the University of Exeter and at Exeter Cathedral.\n\n[[Chris Martin]], who is lead singer of internationally famous band [[Coldplay]], grew up in Countess Wear in the south east of the city.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meritt |first1=Anita |title=Chris Martin and Exeter - why Coldplay dropped album exclusive in city paper |url=https://www.devonlive.com/whats-on/music-nightlife/chris-martin-exeter-coldplay-dropped-3461066 |website=Devon Live |accessdate=29 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029030243/https://www.devonlive.com/whats-on/music-nightlife/chris-martin-exeter-coldplay-dropped-3461066 |archive-date=29 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Museums and Galleries===\n* The [[Royal Albert Memorial Museum]] in Queen Street is Exeter's predominant museum. The museum maintains its own collections of regional, national and international importance. Recently, the museum underwent an extensive refurbishment. It reopened on 14 December 2011, and was subsequently awarded the National Art Fund Prize \u2013 UK Museum of the Year 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Albert Memorial Museum|url=http://www.rammuseum.org.uk/|work=RAM Museum Website|access-date=5 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713150413/http://www.rammuseum.org.uk/|archive-date=13 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The Museum also runs St Nicholas Priory in Mint Lane, near Fore Street. \n* Additionally, the University of Exeter has an extensive fine art collection and an assortment of exhibition spaces across its Streatham campus. Showing a vibrant programme of exhibitions, performances, films and visual arts. The sculpture collection contains works by artists including Barbara Hepworth, Peter Thursby, Geoffrey Clark and Elaine M. Goodwin. It can be located using the Sculpture Trail. \n*Exeter Phoenix is one of South West England's leading contemporary arts venues. The venue occupies the former university site in Gandy Street and programmes international, national and outstanding regional artists.\n* Until its closure in 2017, [[Spacex (art gallery)]], was a contemporary arts organisation, that programmed exhibitions of contemporary art and promoted artist-led projects, events and research.\n\n===Newspapers===\n* ''[[Express and Echo]]'', twice-weekly with a Monday and Thursday edition.\n* ''[[Trewman's Exeter Flying Post|Exeter Flying Post]]'', published weekly. Originally discontinued in 1917, but was revived in 1976 as an alternative community magazine. The last issue was in 2012. \n* ''The [[Western Morning News]]'', a [[Plymouth]] printed daily regional paper. \n* ''[[Exepos\u00e9]]'', the University's student newspaper, printed fortnightly.\n\n===Radio===\n[[BBC Radio Devon]] broadcasts to Exeter locally on FM (95.8) and AM (990 AM/MW), although the majority of programming originates in Plymouth. In the evenings, BBC Radio Devon joins the South West Regional service. [[Heart South West]], formerly [[Gemini FM]] and [[Devonair]], broadcasts on 97.0 FM, with [[East Devon]] and [[Torbay]] utilising their own frequencies. Both Heart South West and BBC Devon broadcast from the St. Thomas transmitter. AM radio is broadcast from Pearce's Hill located at J31 of the M5.\n\nOther radio stations include [[Exeter FM]], an easy listening station broadcasting on 107.3 FM, Phonic.FM which provides a \"no adverts no playlist\" alternative on 106.8 FM or online at www.phonic.fm, VI, a station broadcasting from the West of England School and College on 1386 AM/MW.\n\nAdditionally, Exeter University has a well established student station, [[Xpression FM]], which broadcasts on 87.7 FM using two low-powered transmitters, although it can be heard over much of the north of the city.\n\nThe local [[commercial radio]] station is [[107.3 Radio Exe|Radio Exe]]. The local [[community radio]] station is [[Phonic FM]].\n\n===Television===\nBoth [[BBC Spotlight]] and [[ITV West Country]] provide Exeter with regional news outputs. BBC Spotlight is broadcast from Plymouth and ITV Westcountry is broadcast from Bristol. Although, both services do have newsrooms in Exeter. The St Thomas and [[Stockland Hill transmitting station]] both provide the city's coverage with both transmitters having completed the [[digital switchover]].\n\n===Twin towns===\n[[File:Piazza Terracina, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 236121.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Piazza Terracina, Exeter, named after [[Terracina]], Italy]]\nExeter is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with [[Rennes]] in France,<ref name=\"Archant twinning 3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705094933/http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|title=British towns twinned with French towns ''[via WaybackMachine.com]''|accessdate=20 July 2013|archivedate=5 July 2013|work=Archant Community Media Ltd}}</ref> [[Bad Homburg]] in Germany, [[Yaroslavl]] in Russia, and [[Terracina]] in Italy.<ref name=\"Exeter twinning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=9787|title=Town twinning|publisher=Exeter City Council|accessdate=16 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024180740/http://exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=9787|archivedate=24 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Devon}}\n*[[Exeter (HM Prison)]]\n*[[Henry Phillpotts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources and further reading==\n{{See also|Timeline of Exeter#Bibliography|l1=Bibliography of the history of Exeter}}\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Gray\n|first=Todd\n|title=Exeter: The Traveller's Tales\n|year=2000\n|isbn=1-903356-00-8\n|publisher=The Mint Press\n|location=Exeter}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Higham\n|first= Robert\n|title= Making Anglo-Saxon Devon\n|publisher=The Mint Press\n|year= 2008\n|location= Exeter\n|isbn= 978-1-903356-57-9}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Hoskins\n|first= W. G.\n|authorlink= William George Hoskins\n|title= Two Thousand Years in Exeter\n|publisher=Phillimore\n|location= Chichester\n|year= 2004\n|edition= Revised and updated\n|page= 23\n|isbn= 1-86077-303-6}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Sellman\n|first= R.R.\n|title= Aspects of Devon History\n|publisher=Devon Books\n|location= Exeter\n|year= 1985\n|edition= New\n|isbn= 0-86114-756-1}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Sharp\n|first= Thomas\n|authorlink= Thomas Wilfred Sharp\n|title=Exeter Phoenix: A Plan for Rebuilding\n|year=1946\n|publisher=The Architectural Press\n|location=London}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Stoyle\n|first= Mark\n|authorlink = Mark Stoyle\n|title=Circled With Stone: Exeter's City Walls, 1485\u20131660\n|year=2003\n|publisher=University of Exeter Press\n|location=Exeter\n|isbn= 978-0-85989-727-3}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Stoyle\n|first= Mark\n|title=From Deliverance to Destruction: Rebellion and Civil War in an English City\n|year=1996\n|publisher=University of Exeter Press\n|location=Exeter\n|isbn= 978-0-85989-478-4}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Stoyle\n|first= Mark\n|title=Water in the City: The Aqueducts and Underground Passages of Exeter\n|year=2014\n|publisher=University of Exeter Press\n|location=Exeter\n|isbn= 978-0-85989-877-5}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Exeter}}\n{{wikivoyage}}\n<!-- Links of Dubious Quality will be removed -->\n* [http://www.exeter.gov.uk/ Exeter City Council]\n* [http://genuki.cs.ncl.ac.uk/DEV/Exeter/ExeterHist1850/History.html History of Exeter] from White's Devonshire Directory, 1850\n* {{dmoz|/Regional/Europe/United_Kingdom/England/Devon/Exeter/}}\n* {{OpenDomesday|SX9292|exeter}}\n\n{{SW England}}\n{{UK cities}}\n{{Devon}}\n{{Viking Invasion of England}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Exeter| ]]\n[[Category:Roman fortifications in Devon]]\n[[Category:Cities in South West England]]\n[[Category:County towns in England]]\n[[Category:Non-metropolitan districts of Devon]]\n[[Category:Staple ports]]\n[[Category:Roman legionary fortresses in England]]\n[[Category:Towns in Devon]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Devon]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Short description|City in the south west of England}} \n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Exeter\n| other_name                      = City of Exeter\n| settlement_type                 = [[City status in the United Kingdom|City]] and [[non-metropolitan district]]\n| motto                           = ''[[Semper fidelis]]'' ''(Always Faithful)''\n| image_skyline                   = ExeterCollage.jpg\n| imagesize                       = 280px\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise: The Cathedral, The Clock Tower, Devon County Hall, Cathedral Close, The Iron Bridge.\n<!-- Commented out because image was deleted: |image_blank_emblem      = Arms-exeter.jpg -->| blank_emblem_type               = City Council's Coat of Arms\n| blank_emblem_size               = 256px\n| image_map                       = Exeter UK locator map.svg\n| mapsize                         = 256px\n| map_caption                     = The District of Exeter including Topsham shown within [[Devon]]\n| subdivision_type                = [[List of sovereign states|Sovereign state]]\n| subdivision_name                = United Kingdom\n| subdivision_type1               = [[Countries of the United Kingdom|Constituent country]]\n| subdivision_name1               = England\n| subdivision_type3               = [[Regions of England|Region]]\n| subdivision_name3               = [[South West England]]\n| subdivision_type4               = [[Ceremonial counties of England|Ceremonial]] and [[Metropolitan and non-metropolitan counties of England|shire]] county\n| subdivision_name4               = [[Devon]]\n| government_type                 = City Council\n| governing_body                  = [[Exeter City Council]]\n| leader_title                    = [[Mayor of Exeter|Lord Mayor]]\n| leader_name                     = Peter Holland\n| leader_title1                   = HQ\n| leader_name1                    = Civic Centre, Paris Street\n| leader_title2                   = [[List of MPs elected in the 2019 United Kingdom general election|MPs]]\n| leader_name2                    = [[Ben Bradshaw]] ([[Labour Party (UK)|L]])<br />[[Simon Jupp]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|C]])\n| leader_title3                   = [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK Parliament]]\n| leader_name3                    = [[Exeter (UK Parliament constituency)|Exeter]]<br />[[East Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|East Devon]]\n| established_title               = [[City status in the United Kingdom|City status]]\n| established_date                = ''[[Time immemorial]]''\n| established_title1              = [[Non-metropolitan district]]\n| established_date1               = 1974\n| area_total_km2                  = {{English district area||GSS=E07000041}}\n| area_rank                       = {{English district area rank|GSS=E07000041}} [[List of English districts by area|(of {{English district total}})]]\n| area_footnotes                  = <ref>{{United Kingdom district population citation|area}}</ref>\n| population_total                = {{English district population|GSS=E07000041}}\n| population_as_of                = {{English statistics year}}\n| population_rank                 = {{English district rank|GSS=E07000041}} [[List of English districts by population|(of {{English district total}})]]\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_blank1_title         = [[Demonym]]s\n| population_blank1               = Exonian\n| population_blank2_title         = Ethnicity <small>(2011)</small><ref name=\"ethnicity\">{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=61&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374164893234&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2575|title=Ethnic Group, 2011|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|date=30 January 2013|accessdate=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629170901/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=61&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374164893234&enc=1&dsFamilyId=2575|archive-date=29 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| population_blank2               = {{Collapsible list\n|title                   = 93.05% [[White people|White]]\n|frame_style             = border:none; padding: 0;\n|list_style              = text-align:left;display:none;\n|3                       = 88.32% [[White British]]\n|4                       = 0.53% [[Irish Briton|White Irish]]\n|5                       = 0.08% [[Romani people|Gypsy]] or [[Irish Travellers|Irish Traveller]]\n|6                       = 4.12% [[White Other (United Kingdom Census)|Other White]]\n|7                       = &nbsp;\n|8                       = '''1.65% [[British Mixed|Mixed]]'''\n|9                       = 0.34% [[British Mixed|White & Black Caribbean]]\n|10                      = 0.24% [[British Mixed|White & Black African]]\n|11                      = 0.66% [[British Mixed|White and Asian]]\n|12                      = 0.41% [[British Mixed|Other mixed]]\n|13                      = &nbsp;\n|14                      = '''3.90% [[British Asian|Asian]]'''\n|15                      = 0.80% [[Indian British|Indian]]\n|16                      = 0.14% [[Pakistani British|Pakistani]]\n|17                      = 0.19% [[British Bangladeshi|Bangladeshi]]\n|18                      = 1.70% [[British Chinese|Chinese]]\n|19                      = 1.07% [[British Asian|Other Asian]]\n|20                      = &nbsp;\n|21                      = '''0.57% [[Black British|Black]]'''\n|22                      = 0.42% [[African British|Black African]]\n|23                      = 0.11% [[British African-Caribbean community|Black Caribbean]]\n|24                      = 0.04% [[Black British|Other Black]]\n|25                      = &nbsp;\n|26                      = '''0.83% [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|Other]]'''\n|27                      = 0.56% [[British Arabs|Arab]]\n|28                      = 0.28% [[Other ethnic group (United Kingdom Census)|Other]]\n}}\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>{{United Kingdom district population citation|England}}</ref>\n| timezone                        = [[Greenwich Mean Time|GMT]]\n| utc_offset                      = 0\n| timezone_DST                    = [[British Summer Time|BST]]\n| utc_offset_DST                  = +1\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|50|43|N|3|32|W|region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in the United Kingdom|Postcode district]]\n| postal_code                     = [[EX postcode area|EX1-6]]\n| area_code                       = 01392\n| website                         = {{URL|https://exeter.gov.uk}}\n| official_name                   = \n}}\n'''Exeter''' ({{IPAc-en|audio=en-uk-Exeter.ogg|\u02c8|\u025b|k|s|\u026a|t|\u0259r}}) is a city in [[Devon]], [[England]], on the [[River Exe]] {{convert|36|mi|km}} northeast of [[Plymouth]] and {{convert|65|mi|km}} southwest of [[Bristol]]. It is the [[county town]] of Devon, and home to [[Devon County Council]] and the [[University of Exeter]].\n\nIn [[Roman Britain]], Exeter was established as the base of [[Legio II Augusta]] under the personal command of [[Vespasian]]. Exeter became a religious centre in the [[Middle Ages]]. [[Exeter Cathedral]], founded in the mid 11th century, became [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] in the 16th-century [[English Reformation]]. In the late 19th century, Exeter became an affluent centre for the [[wool trade]], although by the [[First World War]] the city was in decline. After the [[Second World War]], much of the city centre was rebuilt and is now a centre for business and tourism in Devon and Cornwall.\n\nThe administrative area of Exeter has the status of a [[non-metropolitan district]] under the administration of the County Council; a plan to grant the city [[unitary authority]] status was scrapped by the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|2010 coalition government]].\n\n==Name==\nThe modern name of Exeter is a development of the [[Old English]] ''Escanceaster'',<ref name=tcodoepn>{{cite book |title=The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names |author=Eilert Ekwall |publisher=Oxford University Press |year=1981 |page=171 |isbn=0-19-869103-3}}</ref> from the [[Anglicization of names|anglicised]] form of the river now known as the [[River Exe|Exe]] and the Old English [[suffix]] {{nowrap|[[Chester (placename element)|-''ceaster'']]}} (as in [[Dorset#Toponymy|Dorset]] and [[Gloucester#Etymology|Glowcester]]), used to mark important fortresses or fortified towns. (The Welsh name for the city, {{lang|cy|Caerwysg}}, similarly means \"[[caer|''caer'' or fortress]] on the Exe\".) The name \"Exe\" is a separate development of the [[Common Brittonic|Brittonic]] name&mdash;meaning \"water\"<ref>{{cite book |title=The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names |author=Eilert Ekwall |publisher=OUP |location=Oxford [Eng.] |year=1981 |pages=171 |isbn=0-19-869103-3}}</ref> or, more exactly, \"full of fish\" (cf. [[Welsh language|Welsh]] ''pysg'', {{abbr|pl.|Plural}} \"fish\")<ref>Owen, H.W. & Morgan, R. 2007 Dictionary of the Place-names of Wales Gomer Press, Ceredigion; Gwasg Gomer / Gomer Press; page 484.</ref>&mdash;that also appears in the [[England|English]] [[River Axe (Lyme Bay)|Axe]] and [[River Esk, North Yorkshire|Esk]] and the [[Wales|Welsh]] [[River Usk|Usk]] ({{lang-cy|Wysg}}).\n\n==History==\n{{Further|Timeline of Exeter}}\n\n===Prehistory===\n{{see also|Dumnonii|British Iron Age}}\nExeter began as settlements on a dry ridge ending in a spur overlooking a navigable [[River Exe|river]] teeming with fish, with fertile land nearby. Although there have been no major [[Prehistoric Britain|prehistoric]] finds, these advantages suggest the site was occupied early.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 4\u2013}}5.</ref> [[Numismatics|Coins]] have been discovered from the [[Hellenistic period|Hellenistic kingdoms]], suggesting the existence of a settlement trading with the Mediterranean as early as {{nowrap|250 {{sc|bc}}}}.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|p. 1.}}</ref> Such early towns had been a feature of pre-Roman [[Gaul]] as described by [[Julius Caesar]] in his ''[[Commentarii de Bello Gallico|Commentaries]]'' and it is possible that they existed in [[Britannia]] as well.\n[[File:Door through the city walls - geograph.org.uk - 809408.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A portion of Exeter's city wall, formed of both Roman and medieval stones.]]\n\n===Roman times===\n{{Main|Isca Dumnoniorum|Legio II Augusta|Roman Britain}}\nThe [[Ancient Romans|Romans]] established a {{convert|42|acre|ha|adj=on}} 'playing-card' shaped (rectangle with round corners and two short and two long sides) fort ({{lang-la|[[castrum]]}}) named '''[[Isca Dumnoniorum|Isca]]''' around {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;55. The fort was the southwest terminus of the [[Fosse Way]] (Route 15 of the ''[[Antonine Itinerary]]'') and served as the base of the {{nowrap|5&thinsp;000-}}man [[Legio II Augusta|Second Augustan Legion]] ({{lang|la|Legio II Augusta}}) originally led by Vespasian, later Roman Emperor, for the next 20 years before they moved to [[Caerleon]] in [[Wales]], which was also known as [[Isca Augusta|Isca]]. To distinguish the two, the Romans also referred to Exeter as {{nowrap|'''Isca Dumnoniorum'''}}, \"Watertown of the [[Dumnonii]]\", and Caerleon as Isca Augusta. A small fort was also maintained at [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]]; a supply depot on the route between the two was excavated at {{nowrap|St Loyes}} on Topsham Road in 2010.\n\nThe presence of the fort built up an unplanned civilian community ({{lang|la|[[vicus]]}} or {{lang|la|[[canabae]]}}) of [[Britons (Celtic people)|natives]] and the soldiers' families, mostly to the northeast of the fort. This settlement served as the [[civitas|tribal capital]] ({{lang|la|civitas}}) of the [[Dumnonii]]<ref name=bidy>Bidwell, Paul&nbsp;T. ''Roman Exeter: Fortress and Town'', {{nowrap|p.&nbsp;56}}. Exeter City Council (Exeter), 1980. {{ISBN|0-86114-270-5}}.</ref> and was listed as one of their four cities ({{lang-grc-gre|[[poleis]]|script=Latn}}) by [[Claudius Ptolemy|Ptolemy]] in his ''[[Geography (Ptolemy)|Geography]]''<ref name=RBOD>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-britain.org/tribes/dumnonii.htm|title=The Celtic Tribes of Britain: The Dumnonii|publisher=Roman Britain Organisation|accessdate=5 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120708032030/http://www.roman-britain.org/tribes/dumnonii.htm|archive-date=8 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> (it also appeared in the 7th-century ''[[Ravenna Cosmography]]'', where it appears as an apparently [[scribal error|confused]] entry for {{lang|la|Scadu Namorum}}<ref name=RBOID>{{cite web|url=http://www.roman-britain.org/places/isca_dumnoniorum.htm|title=isca dvmnoniorvm|publisher=Roman Britain Organisation|accessdate=5 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120512150808/http://www.roman-britain.org/places/isca_dumnoniorum.htm|archivedate=12 May 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>). When the fortress was abandoned around the year 75, its grounds were converted to civilian purposes: its very large [[thermae|bathhouse]] was demolished to make way for a [[forum (Roman)|forum]] and a [[basilica]], and a smaller-scale bath was erected to the southeast.<ref name=bidy/> This area was excavated in the 1970s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britarch.ac.uk/ba/ba65/feat2.shtml|title=Great Sites: Exeter Roman Baths|work=British Archaeology magazine|date=June 2002|accessdate=12 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200646/http://www.britarch.ac.uk/ba/ba65/feat2.shtml|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/timetrail/02_romanfortress/bath_house.htm |title=The Roman Fortress at Exeter: the Roman Bath House|accessdate=12 July 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080604101008/http://www.exeter.gov.uk/timetrail/02_romanfortress/bath_house.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 4 June 2008}}</ref> but could not be maintained for public view owing to its proximity to the [[Exeter Cathedral|present-day cathedral]]. In January 2015, it was announced that Exeter Cathedral had launched a bid to restore the baths and open an underground centre for visitors.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-30081921 |title=Excavation plans for Exeter's Roman Baths |last=Jones |first=Claire |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=16 January 2015 |access-date=21 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181109221622/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-30081921 |archive-date=9 November 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the late 2nd century, the ditch and rampart defences around the old fortress were replaced by a bank and wall enclosing a much larger area, some 92&nbsp;acres (37&nbsp;ha).<ref name=B59>Bidwell (1980), {{nowrap|p. 59}}.</ref> Although most of the visible structure is older, the course of the Roman wall was used for Exeter's subsequent city walls. Thus about 70% of the Roman wall remains, and most of its route can be traced on foot. The Devonian Isca seems to have been most prosperous in the first half of the 4th century: more than a thousand [[Roman coins]] have been found around the city and there is evidence for copper and bronze working, a stock-yard, and markets for the livestock, crops, and pottery produced in the surrounding countryside.<ref>Bidwell (1980), {{nowrap|pp. 69\u2013}}76 & 80.</ref> The dating of the coins so far discovered, however, suggests a rapid decline: virtually none have been discovered dated after the year 380.<ref>Hoskins, William George. ''Two Thousand Years in Exeter'', rev. ed., {{nowrap|p. 14}}. Phillimore (Chicester), 2004. {{ISBN|1-86077-303-6}}.</ref>\n\n===Medieval times===\n{{see also|Sub-Roman Britain|Saxon England|Norman England}}\n[[Bishop Ussher]] identified the [[caer|Cair]] {{nowrap|Pensa ''vel'' Coyt}}<ref name=mommy>[[Nennius]] ({{abbr|attrib.|Traditional attribution}}). [[Theodor Mommsen]] ({{abbr|ed.|Editor}}). [[s:la:Historia Brittonum#VI. CIVITATES BRITANNIAE|''Historia Brittonum'', VI.]] Composed after {{sc|ad}}&nbsp;830. {{in lang|la}} Hosted at [[s:la:Main Page|Latin Wikisource]].</ref> listed among the 28 [[civitas|cities]] of [[Sub-Roman Britain|Britain]] by the ''[[Historia Brittonum|History of the Britons]]'' as Isca,<ref name=shusher>Newman, John Henry &&nbsp;al. [http://www.mocavo.co.uk/Lives-of-the-English-Saints-St-Gilbert-Prior-of-Sempringham-Volume-3/527392/459 ''Lives of the English Saints: St. German, Bishop of Auxerre'', Ch.&nbsp;X: \"Britain in 429, A.&nbsp;D.\",<!--sic--> p.&nbsp;92.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160321234154/http://www.mocavo.co.uk/Lives-of-the-English-Saints-St-Gilbert-Prior-of-Sempringham-Volume-3/527392/459 |date=21 March 2016 }} James Toovey (London), 1844.</ref> although David Nash Ford read it as a reference to [[Penselwood]] and thought it more likely to be [[Lindinis]] (modern [[Ilchester]]).<ref name=nashford>Ford, David Nash. \"[http://www.britannia.com/history/ebk/articles/nenniuscities.html The 28 Cities of Britain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415120312/http://www.britannia.com/history/ebk/articles/nenniuscities.html |date=15 April 2016 }}\" at Britannia. 2000.</ref> Nothing is certainly known of Exeter from the time of the [[Roman withdrawal from Britain]] around the year 410 until the seventh century.<ref name=\"HOS15\">Hoskins 2004, p. 15</ref> By that time, the city was held by the [[Anglo-Saxons|Saxons]], who had arrived in Exeter after defeating the [[Britons (Celtic people)|British]] [[Dumnonia]]ns at [[Battle of Peonnum|Peonnum]] in [[Somerset]] in 658.<ref>Sellman (1985), {{nowrap|p. 16}}.</ref> It seems likely that the Saxons maintained a quarter of the city for the Britons under their own laws around present-day Bartholomew Street,<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 15\u2013}}16.</ref> which was known as \"Britayne\" Street until 1637 in memory of its former occupants.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|p. 159}}.</ref>\n\nExeter was known to the Saxons as '''Escanceaster'''.<ref name=tcodoepn/> In 876, it was [[Viking invasions of England|attacked and briefly captured]] by [[Danes (ancient people)|Danish]] [[Vikings]]. [[Alfred the Great]] drove them out the next summer.<ref name=\"HOS23\"/> Over the next few years, he elevated Exeter to one of the four ''[[burh]]s'' in Devon, rebuilding its walls on the Roman lines.<ref name=\"SEL17\">Sellman (1985), {{nowrap|p. 17}}.</ref> These permitted the city to fend off another attack and siege by the Danes in 893.<ref name=\"SEL17\"/> [[Athelstan of England|King Athelstan]] again strengthened the walls around 928, and at the same time drove out the remaining [[Britons (historical)|Britons]] from the city.<ref name=\"HOS23\">Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|p. 23}}.</ref> (It is uncertain, though, whether they had lived in the city continuously since the Roman period or returned from the countryside when Alfred strengthened its defences.<ref>Higham (2008), {{nowrap|p. 47}}.</ref>) According to [[William of Malmesbury]], they were sent beyond the [[River Tamar]], which was fixed as the boundary of Devon. (This may, however, have served as a territorial boundary within the former kingdom of [[Dumnonia]] as well.<ref>Higham (2008), {{nowrap|p. 19}}.</ref>) Other references suggest that the British simply moved to what is now the {{nowrap|St. David's}} area, not far outside Exeter's walls. The quarter vacated by the Britons was apparently adapted as \"the [[earl]]'s burh\" and was still named Irlesberi in the 12th century.<ref name=\"HOS23\"/> In 1001, the Danes again failed to get into the city, but they were able to plunder it in 1003 because they were let in, for unknown reasons, by the [[Kingdom of France|French]] [[Reeve (England)|reeve]] of [[Emma of Normandy]], who had been given the city as part of her dowry on her marriage to [[\u00c6thelred the Unready]] the previous year.<ref name=\"HOS23\"/>\n\n[[File:Rougemont Castle Gatehouse, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 333534.jpg|thumb|upright|right|The gatehouse of [[Rougemont Castle]]]]\n\nTwo years after the [[Norman Conquest|Norman conquest of England]], Exeter rebelled against [[William the Conquerer|King William]]. [[Gytha Thorkelsd\u00f3ttir]], the mother of the slain [[Harold Godwinson|King Harold]], was living in the city at the time, and William promptly marched west and [[Siege of Exeter (1068)|initiated a siege]]. After 18 days, William accepted the city's honourable surrender, swearing an oath not to harm the city or increase its [[tax|ancient tribute]]. However, William quickly arranged for the building of [[Rougemont Castle]] to strengthen Norman control over the area. Properties owned by Saxon landlords were transferred into Norman hands and, on the death of [[Leofric (bishop)|Bishop Leofric]] in 1072, the Norman [[Osbern FitzOsbern]] was appointed his successor.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 26\u2013}}27.</ref>\n\nIn 1136, early in [[the Anarchy]], Rougemont Castle was held against [[Stephen of England|King Stephen]] by [[Baldwin de Redvers]]. Redvers submitted only after a three-month siege, not when the three wells in the castle ran dry, but only after the exhaustion of the large supplies of wine that the garrison was using for drinking, baking, cooking, and putting out fires set by the besiegers.<ref>Hoskins (2004), {{nowrap|pp. 31\u2013}}32.</ref> During the siege, King Stephen built an earthen fortification at the site now known (erroneously) as Danes Castle.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_places/danes.php|title=Danes Castle|date=4 November 2009|accessdate=16 September 2012|work=Exeter Memories|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130914203959/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_places/danes.php|archive-date=14 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Exeter medieval bridge.jpg|thumb|left|Remains of the [[medieval Exe Bridge]], built around 1200<ref>{{cite web|title=The Exe Bridge, Exeter|url=http://www.devon.gov.uk/the-exe-bridge.htm|publisher=Devon County Council|accessdate=30 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208235833/http://www.devon.gov.uk/the-exe-bridge.htm|archive-date=8 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>]]\nThe city held a weekly market for the benefit of its citizens from at least 1213, and by 1281 Exeter was the only town in the south-west to have three market days per week. There are also records of seven annual fairs, the earliest of which dates from 1130, and all of which continued until at least the early 16th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/cmh/gaz/devon.html#Exe|title=Online Gazetteer of Markets and Fairs in England & Wales to 1516: Devon|publisher=Centre for Metropolitan History, Institute of Historical Research|accessdate=26 July 2009|last=Letters|first=Samantha|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228181145/http://www.history.ac.uk/cmh/gaz/devon.html#Exe|archive-date=28 December 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the [[Edict of Expulsion|expulsion]] of the Jews of England in 1290, Exeter was home to England's most westerly Jewish community.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Jewish Community of Exeter |url=https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/exeter |publisher=The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot |access-date=2 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702175726/https://dbs.bh.org.il/place/exeter |archive-date=2 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nDuring the high medieval period, both the cathedral clergy and the citizens enjoyed access to sophisticated aqueduct systems which brought pure drinking water into the city from springs in the neighbouring parish of St Sidwell's. For part of their length, these aqueducts were conveyed through a remarkable network of tunnels, or underground passages, which survive largely intact and which may still be visited today.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=Water in the City: The Aqueducts and Underground Passages of Exeter|date=2014|publisher=University of Exeter Press|location=Exeter|isbn=9780859898775|pages=passim}}</ref>\n\nExeter and [[Bristol]] hosted the first recorded Common Council in the Medioeval England.<ref>{{cite book | author = [[James Tait (historian)|James Tait]] | title = The M\u00e9dieval English Borough, Studies on Its Origins and Constitutional History | publisher = [[Manchester University Press]] | year = 1936 | oclc = 1069280340}}. Work cited by {{cite book | author = Richard Holt | author2 = Gervase Rosser | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=gvTgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190 | title = The Medieval Town in England 1200-1540 | page = 190 | language = en | publisher = Routledge | date = June 23, 2014 | isbn = 9781317899815 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511154432/https://books.google.it/books?id=gvTgAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&source=bl&ots=1SidsaVI3P&sig=ACfU3U03tfp7By3vbsC1zh0nyXkl6Hna-g&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj27ZjB4JPiAhXJzqQKHShDDesQ6AEwDXoECAcQAQ%23v=onepage&q=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&f=false | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 11 May 2019 }}.</ref> The first detailed and continuous evidence of its existence and activity was founded after 1345<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=i9xRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PR6&lpg=PR6 | title = The Medi\u00e6val Council of Exeter | publisher = Manchester University Press | year = 1931 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511152302/https://books.google.it/books?id=i9xRAQAAIAAJ&pg=PR6&lpg=PR6&dq=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&source=bl&ots=RYkdDacVr_&sig=ACfU3U3E6iYC3jqJVf0NWbYTRStAaj2iZg&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiunaD045PiAhXBsKQKHRw1B-IQ6AEwCXoECAkQAQ%23v=onepage&q=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&f=false | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 11 May 2019 }}</ref> Formed by twelve \"better and more discreet men\" (in [[Latin]]: ''duodecim meliores''), reelected each year, it was originally designed to control the abuse of the Major and of his four [[Steward (office)|stewards]], which presided respectively the borough court and the provost court. The members of the Common Council come from the same elite of wealthy citizens as did the major and the stewards<ref>{{cite book | author = [[Maryanne Kowaleski]] | url = https://books.google.it/books?id=kKbGc-XSsdEC&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101 | title = Local Markets and Regional Trade in Medieval Exeter | page = 101 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | date = Oct 9, 2003 | isbn = 9780521521956 | OCLC = 49594482 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511150744/https://books.google.it/books?id=kKbGc-XSsdEC&pg=PA101&lpg=PA101&dq=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&source=bl&ots=j_zuIrg7hz&sig=ACfU3U0ApfNAPgHuuttef6MR6dnGraO9Yg&hl=it&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj27ZjB4JPiAhXJzqQKHShDDesQ6AEwDHoECAYQAQ%23v=onepage&q=exeter%2Bmedieval%2Bcouncil&f=false | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 11 May 2019 }}</ref> and this concern introduced a second conflict of interests in the government organism of the city.\n\n===Modern times===\n[[File:Exeter, 1563.jpg|thumb|An illustration of Exeter in 1563, entitled ''Civitas Exoniae (vulgo Excester) urbs primaria in comitatu Devoniae'']]\n; Tudor and Stuart eras\nIn 1537, the city was made a [[county corporate]]. In 1549, the city successfully withstood a month-long siege by the so-called [[Prayer Book Rebellion|Prayer Book rebels]]: Devon and Cornish folk who had been infuriated by the radical religious policies of King Edward VI. The insurgents occupied the suburbs of Exeter, burnt down two of the city gates and attempted to undermine the city walls, but were eventually forced to abandon the siege after they had been worsted in a series of bloody battles with the king's army. A number of rebels were executed in the immediate aftermath of the siege.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=Circled with Stone: Exeter's City Walls, 1485-1660|date=2003|publisher=University of Exeter Press|location=Exeter|isbn=9780859897273|pages=78\u201380, 190\u201391}}</ref> The [[Livery Dole]] [[almshouse]]s and chapel at [[Heavitree]] were founded in March 1591 and finished in 1594.\n\nWhen [[John Hooker (English constitutionalist)|John Hooker]] was appointed to the city payroll in 1561, he created the Court of Orphans as a municipal government for families broken by the premature death of their major economic source. He also was made the Common Council as the legal owner of any estate left to the orphan children of Exeter, until they have reached the age of 21 to be partially paid back.<ref>{{cite web | author = Robert Turner | url = http://www.creditoncourier.co.uk/article.cfm?id=135509&headline=Thorverton%20Society%20members%20heard%20about%20Exeter\u2019s%20fascinating%20history&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 | title = Thorverton Society members heard about Exeter's fascinating history | date = Dec 16, 2018 | archive-url = https://archive.today/20190511133611/http://www.creditoncourier.co.uk/article.cfm?id=135509&headline=Thorverton%20Society%20members%20heard%20about%20Exeter%E2%80%99s%20fascinating%20history&sectionIs=news&searchyear=2018 | archive-date = 11 May 2019 | url-status = live | access-date = 14 August 2019 }}</ref> The orphan tax was used to fund the construction of the Exeter canal.<ref>{{cite publication| author = Charles Carlton | title = John Hooker and Exeter's Court of Orphans | language = en | journal = Huntington Library Quarterly | volume= 36 | issue = 4  | date = August 1973 | pages = 307-316 | jstor=816690 | publisher = University of Pennsylvania Press}}</ref>\n\nThe city's motto, ''[[Semper fidelis]]'', is traditionally held to have been suggested by [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]], in acknowledgement of the city's contribution of ships to help defeat the [[Spanish Armada]] in 1588;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3469|work=Exeter City Council website|title=Exeter's Coat of Arms|accessdate=13 July 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213165222/http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=3469|archivedate=13 February 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> however its first documented use is in 1660. Schools in Exeter teach that the motto was bestowed by Charles II in 1660 at the Restoration due to Exeter's role in the [[English Civil War]].\n\nWhen in 1638 Reverend John Wheelwright was exiled from the [[Massachusetts Bay Colony]] and subsequently established a community on the banks of the [[Squamscott River]], he named the region [[Exeter, New Hampshire|Exeter]] after its Devonian counterpart. During the [[American Revolutionary War|American Revolution]] it became the capital of [[New Hampshire]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://independencemuseum.org/aim_exeter.htm|title=Exeter - Its History|publisher=American Independence Museum|accessdate=March 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309095405/http://www.independencemuseum.org/aim_exeter.htm|archive-date=9 March 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nExeter was secured for Parliament at the beginning of the English Civil War, and its defences very much strengthened, but in September 1643 it was captured by the Cornish Royalist Army led by Prince Maurice. Thereafter, the city remained firmly under the king's control until near the end of the war, being one of the final Royalist cities to fall into Parliamentarian hands.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=From Deliverance to Destruction: Rebellion and Civil War in an English City|date=1996|publisher=University of Exeter Press|location=Exeter|isbn=9780859894784|pages=62\u2013108}}</ref> The surrender of Exeter was negotiated in April 1646 at [[Poltimore House]] by [[Thomas Fairfax]].<ref>{{Cite book|title=Devon|first=W.G.|last=Hoskins|authorlink=William George Hoskins|year=2003|publisher=Phillimore and Co.|pages=196\u2013198|isbn=978-1-86077-270-2}}</ref> During this period, Exeter was an economically powerful city, with a strong trade of [[wool]]. This was partly due to the surrounding area which was \"more fertile and better inhabited than that passed over the preceding day\" according to Count [[Lorenzo Magalotti]] who visited the city when he was 26 years old.<ref>Gray 2000, p.16</ref> Magalotti writes of over thirty thousand people being employed in the county of Devon as part of the wool and cloth industries, merchandise that was sold to \"the West Indies, Spain, France and Italy\".<ref>Gray 2000, p.18</ref> Celia Fiennes also visited Exeter during this period, in the early 1700s. She remarked on the \"vast trade\" and \"incredible quantity\" in Exeter, recording that \"it turns the most money in a week of anything in England\", between \u00a310,000 and \u00a315,000.<ref>Gray 2000, p.31</ref>\n\n; Georgian and Victorian eras\n[[File:Roque's Map of Exeter 1744.jpg|thumb|right|[[John Rocque]]'s 1744 map of Exeter]]\nEarly in the [[Industrial Revolution]], Exeter's industry developed on the basis of locally available agricultural products and, since the city's location on a fast-flowing river gave it ready access to [[water power]], an early industrial site developed on drained marshland to the west of the city, at [[Exe Island]]. However, when [[steam power]] replaced water in the 19th century, Exeter was too far from sources of coal (or iron) to develop further. As a result, the city declined in relative importance and was spared the rapid 19th-century development that changed many historic European cities. Extensive canal redevelopments during this period further expanded Exeter's economy, with \"vessels of 15 to 16 tons burthen [bringing] up goods and merchandise from [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]] to the City [[Exeter Quay|Quay]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=George|authorlink=George Oliver (historian)|title=History of the City of Exeter|year=1861|page=107|isbn=0-217-79997-3}}</ref> In 1778 a new bridge across the Exe was opened to replace the old medieval bridge. Built at a cost of \u00a330,000, it had three arches and was built of stone.<ref name=\"exebridges\"/>\n\n[[File:Thomas-Shapter-HistoryOfCholeraInExeter1832-map.jpg|thumb|left|Frontispiece to Shapter's \"History of the Cholera in Exeter in 1832\"]]\nIn 1832, [[cholera]], which had been erupting all across Europe, reached Exeter. The only known documentation of this event was written by Dr [[Thomas Shapter]], one of the medical doctors present during the epidemic.<ref>{{cite book|last=Shapter|first=Thomas|title=The History of the Cholera in Exeter 1832 |year=1848|isbn=0-85409-674-4}}</ref>\n\nThe first railway to arrive in Exeter was the [[Bristol and Exeter Railway]] that opened a station at [[Exeter St Davids railway station|St Davids]] on the western edge in 1844. The [[South Devon Railway Company]] extended the line westwards to [[Plymouth]], opening their own smaller station at [[Exeter St Thomas railway station|St Thomas]], above Cowick Street. A more central railway station, that at [[Exeter Central railway station|Queen Street]], was opened by the [[London and South Western Railway]] in 1860 when it opened its alternative route to London. Butchers [[Lloyd Maunder]] moved to their present base in 1915, to gain better access to the [[Great Western Railway]] for transportation of [[meat processing|meat products]] to London.\n\n[[File:High Street, Exeter, England, ca. 1895.jpg|thumb|right|The High Street ca. 1895]]\nThe first electricity in Exeter was provided by the Exeter Electric Light Company, which was formed at the end of the 1880s, but it was [[Municipalization|municipalised]] in 1896 and became the City of Exeter Electricity Company.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|page=27}}</ref>\n\nThe first [[Exeter tram system|horse-drawn trams in Exeter]] were introduced in 1882 with 3 lines radiating from the city's East Gate. One line went to St David's station via New North Road, the Obelisk (where the Clock Tower now stands) and St David's Hill. The second line went out along Heavitree Road to Livery Dole and the third went to Mount Pleasant along Sidwell Street. There was a depot off New North Road.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=18\u201319}}</ref>\n\n{{clear left}}\n\n===20th century===\n[[File:Lamp standard and ferry, Exeter Quay - geograph.org.uk - 836757.jpg|thumb|left|Lamp standard from the 1905 Exe bridge, installed at [[Butts Ferry]] on [[Exeter Quayside]] in 1983]]\nOn 29 March 1905, a new bridge across the Exe was opened replacing the former Georgian bridge. Made of [[cast-iron]] and steel with a [[Truss arch bridge|three hinged arch]] design, it cost \u00a325,000 and was designed by [[John Wolfe-Barry|Sir John Wolfe Barry]].<ref name=\"exebridges\">{{cite web |url = http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exebridge.php |title = History of the Exe Bridges |work = Exeter Memories |accessdate = 15 September 2012 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120723104916/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exebridge.php |archive-date = 23 July 2012 |url-status = live }}</ref> Also in 1905 [[Exeter Corporation Tramways|electric trams]] replaced the horse trams<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|page=30}}</ref> with a new route which passed along the High Street, down Fore Street and over the new Exe Bridge. Once over the Exe the line divided, with one route along Alphington Road and another along Cowick Street. The line to St David's Station travelled along Queen Street instead of along New North Road and the line to Heavitree was extended.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=86\u201389}}</ref> On 17 March 1917, a tram went out of control going down Fore Street, hit a horse-drawn wagon, then overturned on Exe Bridge and one female passenger was killed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=76\u201378}}</ref> By the 1920s, there were problems with congestion caused by the trams, a need for expensive track renewal work and the slow speed of the trams in Exeter's narrow streets. After much discussion, the council decided to replace the tram service with double-decker buses and the last tram ran on 19 August 1931. The only remaining Exeter tram in service is car 19, now at the [[Seaton Tramway]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Neville|first=Julia|title=Exeter and the Trams 1882\u20131931|year=2010|publisher=Exeter Civic Society|isbn=978-0-9544343-1-1|pages=104\u2013124}}</ref>\n\nExeter was bombed by the German Luftwaffe in the Second World War when a total of 18 raids between 1940 and 1942 flattened much of the city centre. \nBetween April 1941 and April 1943 Exeter was defended from enemy bombers by the Polish 307 Squadron, night-fighters nicknamed the 'Lw\u00f3w Eagle Owls' who were based at Exeter Airport. \nThe city of Lw\u00f3w shared the same motto as the city of Exeter - 'Semper Fidelis' (Always faithful).\n\nIn April and May 1942, as part of the Baedeker Blitz and specifically in response to the RAF bombing of L\u00fcbeck and Rostock, 40 acres (16 ha) of the city, particularly adjacent to its central High Street and Sidwell Street, were levelled by incendiary bombing. Many historic buildings in the heart of the city were destroyed and others, including the Cathedral, were damaged. On the night of 4 May, the only hope that Exeter had to avoid total destruction was the heavily outnumbered Polish 307 Squadron which had four available aircraft against the forty German Junkers-88 bombers. During the next 75 minutes, the squadron prevented four German bombers releasing their load of bombs on Exeter. The squadron suffered no casualties in the process. \n156 people were killed in the attacks,[51]however a lot more people in Exeter would have been killed, and the effect on the city much greater had it not been for the \u2018Lw\u00f3w Eagle Owls\u2019.\n\nTo demonstrate British-Polish cooperation and the friendship that had formed between 307 Squadron and Exeter, the squadron presented the city with a Polish flag on 15 November 1942 (the first British city to have had that honour) outside Exeter Cathedral.\n\nSince 2012 a Polish flag is raised over the city's Guildhall on 15 November in honour of 307 Squadron, the day is now known as '307 Squadron Day' in Exeter.\nOn 15 November 2017, a plaque in memory of the squadron was unveiled in the St James Chapel of Exeter Cathedral by the Polish Ambassador His Excellency Arkady Rzegocki.\n\nLarge areas of the city centre were rebuilt in the 1950s when little attempt was made to preserve Exeter's heritage. Damaged buildings were generally demolished rather than restored, and the street plan was altered in an attempt to improve traffic circulation. Former landmarks such as St. Lawrence, the College of the Vicars Choral & Bedford circus disappeared. The modern architecture stands in sharp contrast to the red sandstone of buildings that survived the Blitz.<ref name=payne>{{cite book|title=The West Country: A Cultural History|first=John|last=Payne|p=176|publisher=Andrews UK Limited|year=2011|isbn=978-1-908-49350-7}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Exe Flood Relief Channel - geograph.org.uk - 695255.jpg|thumb|Exe Flood Relief Channel built after the floods of 1960]]\nOn 27 October 1960, following very heavy rain, the Exe overflowed and flooded large areas of Exeter including Exwick, St Thomas and Alphington. The water rose as high as 2 metres above ground level in places and 150 employees of the local firm Beach Bros were trapped for nine hours. 2,500 properties were flooded. Later the same year on 3 December the river levels rose again, flooding 1,200 properties. These floods led to the construction of new [[flood defences]] for Exeter. Work began in 1965, took 12 years to complete and cost \u00a38 million. The defences included three flood relief channels, and were complemented by the construction of two new concrete bridges (built in 1969 and 1972) to replace the old Exe Bridge which had obstructed the flow of the river and made the flooding worse.<ref>{{cite web\n | title        = The Exeter floods of the 1960s\n | url        = http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exeter_floods.php\n | work        = Exeter Memories\n | date        = 28 October 2010\n | accessdate        = 15 September 2012\n | archive-url        = https://web.archive.org/web/20121028034133/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/exeter_floods.php\n | archive-date        = 28 October 2012\n | url-status        = live\n }}</ref>\n\n===21st century===\nThe [[Princesshay]] shopping centre adjoining the [[Cathedral Close, Exeter|Cathedral Close]] and the High Street was redeveloped between 2005 and 2007,<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Doors open at Princesshay\n |url          = http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/content/articles/2007/09/19/princesshay_opening_day_feature.shtml\n |publisher    = BBC Devon\n |date         = 20 September 2007\n |accessdate   = 21 September 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20080217211042/http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/content/articles/2007/09/19/princesshay_opening_day_feature.shtml\n |archive-date = 17 February 2008\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | title       = Heaven for shoppers as Princesshay gets off to a flying start with huge crowds for opening day\n | url         = http://www.thisisexeter.co.uk/displayNode.jsp?nodeId=142326&command=displayContent&sourceNode=142321&contentPK=18452155&folderPk=79876&pNodeId=142331\n | work   = [[Express & Echo]]\n | date        = 21 September 2007\n | accessdate  = 21 September 2007\n}}</ref> despite some local opposition.<ref>{{cite news\n |title        = High Street revamp plans criticised\n |url          = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2817257.stm\n |publisher    = [[BBC News Online]]\n |date         = 4 March 2003\n |accessdate   = 21 September 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20030819112856/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2817257.stm\n |archive-date = 19 August 2003\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref> It incorporates 123 varied residential units.<ref>{{cite web\n |title        = Key facts about Princesshay\n |url          = http://www.princesshay.com/community/Keyfacts/index.aspx\n |publisher    = Land Securities Group\n |work         = Princesshay.com\n |accessdate   = 21 September 2007\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071014035943/http://princesshay.com/community/Keyfacts/index.aspx\n |archive-date = 14 October 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nTo enable people with limited mobility to enjoy the city, Exeter Community Transport Association provides manual and powered wheelchairs and scooters (called Shopmobility) for use by anyone suffering from short or long-term mobility impairment to access to the city centre and shopping facilities, events and meetings with friends and company.<ref>{{cite web\n | title       = Shopmobility\n | url       = http://www.exetercta.co.uk/shopmobility.asp\n | work       = Exeter Community Transport Association\n | accessdate       = 13 July 2008\n | archive-url       = https://web.archive.org/web/20120406220728/http://www.exetercta.co.uk/shopmobility.asp\n | archive-date       = 6 April 2012\n | url-status       = dead\n }}</ref>\n\nIn May 2008 there was an [[22 May 2008 Exeter bombing|attempted terrorist attack]] on the Giraffe cafe in Princesshay, but the bomber was the only one injured.<ref>{{cite news\n |title        = Nail-bomber given life sentence\n |url          = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7859887.stm\n |publisher    = [[BBC News Online]]\n |date         = 30 January 2009\n |accessdate   = 15 September 2012\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090217020915/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7859887.stm\n |archive-date = 17 February 2009\n |url-status     = live\n}}</ref>\n\nA \u00a330 million improvement scheme for the flood defences was approved in March 2015. The plans involve the removal of [[Check dam|check weirs]] and a deeper, \"meandering stream\" in the centre of the drainage channels to improve flow. The plans followed a study by the [[Environment Agency]] that revealed weaknesses in the current defences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exeter-flood-defence-scheme/exeter-flood-defence-scheme|title=Exeter flood defence scheme|access-date=30 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150530163203/https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/exeter-flood-defence-scheme/exeter-flood-defence-scheme|archive-date=30 May 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[community currency]] for the city, the [[Exeter Pound]], was introduced in 2015<ref>{{cite news|title=Exeter Pound: City launches its own currency|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-34112438|work=BBC News|date=1 September 2015|access-date=21 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180717092757/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-34112438|archive-date=17 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> and dissolved in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=2018-12-06|title=Home Page - Exeter Pound|url=http://www.exeterpound.org.uk/|website=www.exeterpound.org.uk|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181207050042/http://www.exeterpound.org.uk/|archive-date=7 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA serious fire broke out in buildings in central Exeter on 28 October 2016. The fire largely damaged the [[Royal Clarence Hotel]], considered the first venue in England to call itself a hotel. Other historic buildings, including 18 Cathedral Yard and The Well House Tavern,<ref>[http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/historic-building-next-to-destroyed-exeter-hotel-mourns-loss-of-irreplaceable-interior/story-29851231-detail/story.html  \"Architecture experts mourn loss of \"irreplaceable\" interior in building where fire started\", ''Express & Echo'', 29 October 2016] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161030150843/http://www.exeterexpressandecho.co.uk/historic-building-next-to-destroyed-exeter-hotel-mourns-loss-of-irreplaceable-interior/story-29851231-detail/story.html |date=30 October 2016 }}. Retrieved 29 October 2016</ref> were also severely damaged.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-37796576 Exeter fire wrecks 'oldest hotel in England'] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181025070740/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-37796576 |date=25 October 2018 }} ''[[BBC]]''</ref><ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/oct/28/exeter-fire-threatens-royal-clarence-hotel Exeter blaze destroys hotel thought to be oldest in Britain] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161029113249/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/oct/28/exeter-fire-threatens-royal-clarence-hotel |date=29 October 2016 }} ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref> All of the damaged buildings are currently undergoing a major restoration. On 22 February 2017 archaeologists involved in the restoration and repair works of The Royal Clarence Hotel, 18 Cathedral Yard, and The Well House Tavern Pub unearthed medieval pictures, including one of a peacock. The work which had taken three months to complete the process of the deconstruction of the buildings, with every effort being made to save as many historical features as possible. It will take a total of 21 months to restore the fa\u00e7ade external of the buildings and a modern design planned for their interiors of the hotel and 18 Cathedral Yard.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.devonlive.com/royal-clarence-hotel-could-reopen-in-21-months/story-30154366-detail/story.html|title=Royal Clarance Hotel could reopen in 21 months|date=22 February 2017|newspaper=Devon Live|language=en-GB|access-date=30 March 2018}}</ref> On 25 July 2017 the official restoration plans of how the repaired and restored buildings will look once completed, were officially unveiled to the public for the exterior frontal fa\u00e7ade of the buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-40718707|title=Fire-hit 'oldest hotel in England' restoration unveiled|date=25 July 2017|newspaper=[[BBC News]]|language=en-GB|access-date=30 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171103232041/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-devon-40718707|archive-date=3 November 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Further plans were still underway for the interior of the hotel and surrounding buildings the restoration and repair works are being undertaken by construction consultants Thomasons, in partnership with [[Manchester]] architects Buttress, [[Historic England]] and [[Exeter City Council]]. The rebuild was expected to be completed in 18 months with a scheduled reopening of the hotel in 2019. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boutiquehotelier.com/royal-clarence-hotel-reveals-plans-restoration-last-years-fire/|title=The Royal Clarence Hotel reveals plans for restoration after last year\u2019s fire|date=26 July 2017|newspaper=Boutique Hotelier|language=en-GB|access-date=30 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001182347/http://www.boutiquehotelier.com/royal-clarence-hotel-reveals-plans-restoration-last-years-fire/|archive-date=1 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 November 2019 it was reported that 18 Cathedral Yard had now been repaired having undergone a three-year complete restoration undertaken by the same restorers who restored [[Windsor Castle]] following the [[1992 Windsor Castle fire|1992 fire]] in [[Berkshire]], which was completed in November 1997. There is now a second round of bids for the sale and restoration work to complete the repairs of The Well House Tavern Pub and The Royal Clarence Hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/company-confirms-made-offer-exeter-3514221|title=Company confirms it has made an offer for Exeter Royal Clarence fire site - but doesn\u2019t have hotel plans|date=8 November 2019|newspaper=Devon Live|language=en-GB|access-date=12 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108134713/https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/company-confirms-made-offer-exeter-3514221|archive-date=8 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Exeter Combined Court Centre.jpg|thumb|right|The Exeter Crown and County Courts Building.]]\n[[File:Civic Centre, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 271614.jpg|thumb|upright|Exeter Civic Centre]]\nExeter is in two parliamentary constituencies, the majority of the city is in the [[Exeter (UK Parliament constituency)|Exeter constituency]] but two wards (St Loyes and Topsham) are in [[East Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|East Devon]]. Exeter itself is relatively marginal, and since World War II its Member of Parliament has usually been drawn from the governing party, though the Exeter seat is becoming increasingly a Labour stronghold.  The Exeter MP is [[Ben Bradshaw]] and [[Simon Jupp]] represents East Devon. Exeter is part of the [[South West England (European Parliament constituency)|South West England European constituency]], which elects 6 [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s. In 2014, a majority of Exeter voters voted for Labour in the European elections, but in 2019 Labour fell to fourth - the Brexit Party won 28.1% of votes in the city and the Greens won 27.2%.\n\nExeter's [[city council]] is a [[Non-metropolitan district|district]] authority, and shares responsibility for local government with the [[Devon County Council]]. In May 2012 Labour became the majority party on the council. [[Exeter City Council]]'s bid for the city to become a [[Unitary Authority]] was initially approved by ministers in February 2010. A judicial review was called by Devon County Council and the Court held that the Minister had acted unlawfully in granting Unitary status to Exeter at the same time, however, following the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|new coalition government]] announced in May 2010 that the reorganisation would be blocked.<ref name=coalition>{{cite web |url=http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/@dg/@en/documents/digitalasset/dg_187876.pdf |format=PDF |title=The Coalition: our programme for government |publisher=HM Government, United Kingdom |date=20 May 2010 |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612015906/http://www.direct.gov.uk/prod_consum_dg/groups/dg_digitalassets/%40dg/%40en/documents/digitalasset/dg_187876.pdf |archivedate=12 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/liberaldemocrats/7753762/The-Queens-Speech-Bill-by-Bill.html | title= The Queen's Speech: Bill by Bill | date= 22 May 2010 | accessdate= 24 May 2010 | newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] | first= Patrick | last= Hennessy | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100525102927/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/politics/liberaldemocrats/7753762/The-Queens-Speech-Bill-by-Bill.html | archive-date= 25 May 2010 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nFrom Saxon times, it was in the [[Hundred (county subdivision)|hundred]] of [[Wonford (hundred)|Wonford]].<ref name=\"genuki-devonhundreds\">{{cite web | url=http://genuki.cs.ncl.ac.uk/DEV/Hundreds.html | title=The hundreds of devon | work=GENUKI | accessdate=18 June 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427064112/http://genuki.cs.ncl.ac.uk/DEV/Hundreds.html | archive-date=27 April 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Exeter has had a [[Mayor of Exeter|mayor]] since at least 1207 and until 2002, the city was the oldest 'Right Worshipful' Mayoralty in England. As part of the [[Golden Jubilee of Elizabeth II]] Exeter was chosen to receive the title of [[Lord Mayor]]. Councillor Granville Baldwin became the first Lord Mayor of Exeter on 1 May 2002 when [[Letters Patent]] were awarded to the city during a visit by the Queen.\nThe Lord Mayor is elected each year from amongst the 39 Exeter city [[councillor]]s and is non-political for the term of office.\n\n===Public services===\nPolicing in Exeter is provided by the [[Devon and Cornwall Constabulary]] who have their headquarters at Middlemoor in the east of the city.\n\nThe [[fire service]] is provided by the [[Devon and Somerset Fire and Rescue Service]], which is headquartered at Clyst St. George near Exeter. It has two fire stations located at Danes Castle and Middlemoor.\n\nThe [[Royal Devon and Exeter NHS Foundation Trust]] has a large hospital located to the south-east of the city centre. Ambulance services in Exeter are provided by [[South Western Ambulance Service]] NHS Trust. The West Trust Divisional HQ and 999 control is in Exeter which provides cover for [[Devon]], Cornwall, [[Somerset]] and the [[Isles of Scilly]].\n\n==Geography==\n{{see also|List of places in Exeter}}\n[[File:River Exe at Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 258229.jpg|thumb|left|The River Exe]]\n\nThe city of Exeter was established on the eastern bank of the [[River Exe]] on a ridge of land backed by a steep hill. It is at this point that the Exe, having just been joined by the [[River Creedy]], opens onto a wide [[flood plain]] and estuary which results in quite common flooding. Historically this was the [[lowest bridging point]] of the River Exe which was tidal and navigable up to the city until the construction of weirs later in its history. This combined with the easily defensible higher ground of the ridge made the current location of the city a natural choice for settlement and trade. In [[George Oliver (historian)|George Oliver]]'s ''The History of the City of Exeter'', it is noted that the most likely reasons for the original settling of what would become modern Exeter was the \"fertility of the surrounding countryside\" and the area's \"beautiful and commanding elevation [and] its rapid and navigable river\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Oliver|first=George|title=History of the City of Exeter|year=1861|page=1|isbn=0-217-79997-3}}</ref>\nIts woodland would also have been ideal for natural resources and hunting.\n\nExeter sits predominantly on sandstone and conglomerate geology, although the structure of the surrounding areas is varied.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/erdp/docs/swchapter/section11/topography.htm|title=Southwest EDRP Geographical Area and Physical Context|last=DEFRA|accessdate=13 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081113123623/http://www.defra.gov.uk/erdp/docs/swchapter/section11/topography.htm|archive-date=13 November 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>\nThe topography of the ridge which forms the backbone of the city includes a [[volcanic plug]], on which the [[Rougemont Castle]] is situated. The Cathedral is located on the edge of this ridge and is therefore visible for a considerable distance.\n{{Clear}}\n\nExeter is {{convert|80|mile}} west-southwest of [[Salisbury]], {{convert|158|mile}} west-southwest of [[London]], {{convert|18|mile}} north of [[Torquay]], {{convert|36|mile}} northeast of Plymouth and {{convert|74|mile}} east-northeast of [[Truro]].\n\n===Climate===\nExeter has mild wet winters and warm changeable summers with hot and cooler rainy spells. Temperatures do not vary much throughout the year. The hottest month is July with an average high of {{convert|21.7|C|F|}}, and the coldest month is January with an average high of {{convert|8.8|C|F|}}. October is the wettest month with {{convert|88.9|mm|in|}} of rain. Because of shelter from [[Dartmoor]], Exeter is more frost-prone than areas to the southwest, such as [[Plymouth]]. It is also drier, and warmer in the summer for the same reason. The highest recorded temperature in Exeter stands at {{convert|33.5|C|F|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=12&year=1976&indexid=TXx&stationid=2132|title=June 1976|accessdate=5 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311104033/http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=12&year=1976&indexid=TXx&stationid=2132|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> recorded in June 1976, whilst the lowest recorded temperature in Exeter is {{convert|-16.4|C|F|}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=18&year=2010&indexid=TNn&stationid=2132|title=December 2010|accessdate=5 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311103528/http://eca.knmi.nl/utils/indicesmapdetail.php?seasonid=18&year=2010&indexid=TNn&stationid=2132|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> recorded in December 2010.\n\n{{Exeter weatherbox}}\n\n==Demographics==\nFrom the 2011 Census, the [[Office for National Statistics]] published that Exeter's district area population was 117,773;<ref name=census2011keyfigures>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=62&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374189518359&enc=1|title=Key Figures for 2011 Census: Key Statistics|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=18 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629193546/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=62&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374189518359&enc=1|archive-date=29 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> 6,697 more people than that of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|last census]] from 2001, which indicated that Exeter had a population of 111,076.<ref name=\"census 2001\">{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374187787050&enc=1|title=Key Figures for 2001 Census: Key Statistics|accessdate=19 July 2013|work=[[United Kingdom Census 2001|Census 2001]]|publisher=The [[Office for National Statistics]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221162838/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374187787050&enc=1|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> At the time of the 2011 UK census, the ethnic composition of Exeter's population was 93.1% [[White people|White]], with the largest minority ethnic group being [[British Chinese|Chinese]] at 1.7%.<ref name=\"ethnicity\"/> The White British, White Irish and other ethnic group all declined in numbers since the 2001 census (\u22121%, -6% and \u221210% respectively). Meanwhile, the Chinese and ''Other Asian'' had the largest increases (429% and 434% respectively).<ref name=\"ethnicity\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374188868015&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47|title=Ethnic Group, 2001|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|date=9 November 2004|accessdate=19 July 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140629164315/http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=15&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1374188868015&enc=1&dsFamilyId=47|archive-date=29 June 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> This excludes the two new ethnic groups added to the 2011 census of Gypsy or Irish Traveller and Arab. Below are the 10 largest immigrant groups in Exeter {{As of|2011|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"ethnicity\"/>\n{|\n! Country of Birth\n! Immigrants in Exeter (2011 Census)\n|-\n|{{flag|China}}\n|1,665\n|-\n|{{flag|Poland}}\n|1,296\n|-\n|{{flag|Germany}}\n|710\n|-\n|{{flag|India}}\n|653\n|-\n|{{flag|Ireland}}\n|469\n|-\n|{{flag|South Africa}}\n|438\n|-\n|{{flag|USA}}\n|350\n|-\n|{{flag|France}}\n|310\n|-\n|{{flag|Philippines}}\n|295\n|-\n|{{flag|Australia}}\n|242\n|-\n|}\n\nIn 2011, the City of Exeter had a population of 117,773, while its inner urban subdivision had a population of 113,507. The Exeter USD does not include the outlying suburb of [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]], which while it is administratively part of the city, it is often considered a separate individual settlement as well as the fact its excluded from the city's constituency.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Exeter compared 2011 !! Exeter USD !! Exeter City\n|-\n| White British || 88.1% || 88.3%\n|-\n| Asian || 4.0% || 3.9%\n|-\n| Black || 0.6% || 0.5%\n|}\n\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/ks201ew|title=Official Labour Market Statistics|work=nomisweb.co.uk|access-date=19 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161022095240/https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/census/2011/ks201ew|archive-date=22 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, 11.9% of the population of the Exeter USD (urban subdivision) were non white British, compared with 11.7% for the actual city and surrounding borough of Exeter.\n\nIn 2009, Exeter City was 89.1% [[White British]], compared with 88.3% in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadPage.do?pageId=1001&tc=1462006029195&a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=13&f=27655&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1004x1005&l=1812&o=322&m=0&r=1&s=1462006029195&enc=1|title=Neighbourhood Statistics|date=14 April 2008|work=neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk|access-date=30 April 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006120301/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadPage.do?pageId=1001&tc=1462006029195&a=7&b=6275100&c=exeter&d=13&e=13&f=27655&g=6415645&i=1001x1003x1004x1005&l=1812&o=322&m=0&r=1&s=1462006029195&enc=1|archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe Exeter Urban Area had a population of 124,079<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citypopulation.de/UK-EnglandUA.html?cityid=7160|title=United Kingdom: Urban Areas in England - Population Statistics in Maps and Charts|access-date=1 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160413000227/http://www.citypopulation.de/UK-EnglandUA.html?cityid=7160|archive-date=13 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> in 2014, compared with 124,328 for the city and borough of Exeter. While the Exeter Metropolitan Area had a population of 467,257 in the same year and includes Exeter along with [[Teignbridge]], [[Mid Devon]] and [[East Devon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.exetercityfutures.com/exeter-travel-work-area/|title=What is the Exeter Travel to Work Area? - Exeter City Futures|date=1 November 2016|access-date=2 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426031828/https://www.exetercityfutures.com/exeter-travel-work-area/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Out of all the Devon districts, Exeter receives the largest number of commuters from East Devon, followed by Teignbridge. Most of the city's ethnic minority population live in the central, northwestern and eastern suburbs of the city. Outlying areas such as [[Pinhoe]], [[Cowick, Devon|Cowick]] and the expensive suburb of [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]] are all 95% White British as of 2011.\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:Cathedral from Princesshay 3.JPG|thumb|right|Princesshay Shopping Centre with Exeter Cathedral in the background]]\n[[File:A Middle East Soldier Revisits Britain- Life in Wartime Exeter, Devon, England, UK, October 1943 D16650.jpg|thumb|The Higher Market, Exeter, in 1943; at this time the larger firms such as [[Mac Fisheries]] had joined the smaller shopkeepers' stalls in the market, which, before the war, along with neighbouring Goldsmith Street, was earmarked for demolition; a new Civic Centre was to be built on the site]] \nThe [[Met Office]], the main weather forecasting organisation for the United Kingdom and one of the most significant in the world, relocated from [[Bracknell]] in Berkshire to Exeter in early 2004. It is one of the largest employers in the area (together with the [[University of Exeter]], [[Devon County Council]] and the [[Royal Devon and Exeter NHS Foundation Trust]]).\n\nAround 35,000 people commute into Exeter on a daily basis, from nearby surrounding towns.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1002 | title=Exeter commuters | publisher=Exeter City Council | accessdate=1 June 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807120416/http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=1002 | archive-date=7 August 2011 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Exeter provides services, employment and shopping for local residents within the city limits and also from nearby towns in [[Teignbridge]], [[Mid Devon]] and [[East Devon]], together sometimes known as the Exeter & Heart of Devon area (EHOD). Exeter therefore provides for the EHOD area population of 457,400.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.indevon.org.uk/web/uploads/documents/Exeter%20Economic%20Trends%20Feb%2009.pdf | title=EHOD population | publisher=Exeter City Council | accessdate=1 February 2009 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130904173101/http://www.indevon.org.uk/web/uploads/documents/Exeter%20Economic%20Trends%20Feb%2009.pdf | archive-date=4 September 2013 | url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nExeter has been identified among the top ten most profitable locations for a business to be based.<ref>Dun & Bradstreet, 2001</ref>\n\nThe city centre provides substantial shopping facilities. The High Street is mainly devoted to branches of national chains: a [[New Economics Foundation|NEF]] survey in 2005 rated Exeter as the worst example of a [[clone town]] in the UK, with only a single independent store in the city's High Street, and less diversity (in terms of different categories of shop) than any other town surveyed. In 2010, a similar survey reported the city was still the worst clone town.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/traders-hit-clone-town-attack/story-11755773-detail/story.html|title=Traders hit back after 'clone town' attack|work=Western Morning News|date=15 September 2010|accessdate=15 August 2016}}{{Dead link|date=August 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Three significant shopping areas that connect to the High Street provide a somewhat more varied menu. [[Princesshay]], a [[post-war]] retail area connecting to the south side of the High Street was home to a number of independent stores prior to redevelopment in 2007, but is now also largely occupied by national chains. It is still intended that a number of the new units will be let to local independent stores.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} The [[House of Fraser]] building on the high street has been bought buy a local wealth performance management firm, Prydis, who have released their plans to redevelop the building as a 3-storey hotel with a rooftop bar and retail shops.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/first-pictures-house-fraser-plans-2743509|title=First pictures of House of Fraser plans show dramatic rooftop bar|last=Smith|first=Colleen|date=2019-04-10|website=devonlive|access-date=2019-11-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190411161754/https://www.devonlive.com/news/devon-news/first-pictures-house-fraser-plans-2743509|archive-date=11 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn the other side of the High Street, the partly undercover Guildhall Shopping Centre houses a mixture of national and more regional shops, and connects to the wholly enclosed Harlequins Centre where smaller businesses predominate. Smaller streets off the High Street such as Gandy Street also offer a range of independent shops.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}\n\nOn 26 June 2004, Exeter was granted [[Fairtrade City]] status.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://exeter.gov.uk/people-and-communities/communities/fairtrade/|title=Fairtrade - Exeter City Council|website=www.exeter.gov.uk|access-date=2019-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190416050343/https://exeter.gov.uk/people-and-communities/communities/fairtrade/|archive-date=16 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Exeter contains a number of tourist attractions, the city is not dominated by tourism, with only 7% of employment dependent on tourism compared with 13% for Devon as a whole (2005 figures).<ref>[http://www.tourisminsights.info/STATISTICS/STAT1.HTML South West Tourism (2006)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420021523/http://www.tourisminsights.info/STATISTICS/STAT1.HTML |date=20 April 2009 }}, ''The Value of Tourism in Devon 2005''. Exeter: SWT</ref>\n\nThere are also plans to build on land in the Teignbridge and East Devon areas, which border Exeter's boundaries, as part of the \"Exeter Growth Point\" strategy, which includes the [[New towns in the United Kingdom|new town]] of [[Cranbrook, Devon|Cranbrook]] located about 5 miles the east of the city in East Devon where construction began in 2011 and is now home to several thousand residents.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/South-West-Exeter/ | title=Exeter Growth Point | date=1 January 2011 | publisher=Devon County Council | accessdate=1 January 2011 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110521050555/http://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/South-West-Exeter/ | archive-date=21 May 2011 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastdevon.gov.uk/planning/planning-policy/cranbrook-plan/the-development-of-cranbrook-and-the-cranbrook-plan/|title=Cranbrook Plan|website=East Devon|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426031830/http://www.eastdevon.gov.uk/planning/planning-policy/cranbrook-plan/the-development-of-cranbrook-and-the-cranbrook-plan/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/Cranbrook/|title=Cranbrook - Exeter and East Devon Growth Point|website=www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk|access-date=2019-04-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190426031834/https://www.exeterandeastdevon.gov.uk/Cranbrook/|archive-date=26 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n{{further|Grade I listed buildings in Exeter|Grade II* listed buildings in Exeter}}\n{{wide image|Exeter panorama 1.jpg|900px|A panorama of the city taken from the roof of the north tower of the cathedral}}\nAmong the notable buildings in Exeter are:\n\n===Religious buildings===\n[[File:ExeterCathedral-4.jpg|thumb|[[Exeter Cathedral]] and the [[Devon County War Memorial]]]]\n{{See also|Exeter#Religion}}\n* The [[Exeter Cathedral|cathedral]], founded in 1050 when the bishop's seat was moved from the nearby town of [[Crediton]] (birthplace of [[Saint Boniface]]) because Exeter's Roman walls offered better protection against \"pirates\", presumably [[Viking]]s. A statue of [[Richard Hooker (theologian)|Richard Hooker]], the 16th century [[Anglican]] theologian, who was born in Exeter, has a prominent place in the [[Cathedral Close, Exeter|Cathedral Close]].\n* [[St Nicholas Priory]] in Mint Lane, the remains of a [[monastery]], later used as a private house and now a museum owned by the city council. The priory was founded in 1087 and was home to Benedictine monks for over 400 years, until it was closed and partly demolished by [[Henry VIII]]. The remaining buildings were then sold off in 1602 and became the home of the locally wealthy Hurst family. The property has been fully renovated by Exeter City Council, and the small garden area features Tudor plants and herbs<ref>''St Nicholas Priory: Discover a Tudor Home'' Booklet produced by Exeter City Council (July 2009)</ref>\n* A number of medieval churches including [[St Mary Steps, Exeter|St Mary Steps]] which has an elaborate clock.\n* The [[Exeter Synagogue]] is the third oldest synagogue in Britain, completed in 1763.\n*[[St Thomas' Church, Exeter|St Thomas' Church]], originally built in the 13th century just outside the city walls. Destroyed by fire and rebuilt in the 17th century; grade I listed.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1169954|desc=Church of St Thomas|accessdate=4 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Exeter, Kathedrale St. Peter -- 2013 -- 1.jpg|900px|A panorama of Exeter Cathedral and [[Cathedral Close, Exeter|Cathedral Close]]}}\n\n===Secular buildings===\n[[File:The House that Moved in Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 1727313.jpg|thumb|upright|\"The House that Moved\", West Street, Exeter]]\n* The [[ruins]] of [[Rougemont Castle]], built soon after the [[Norman Conquest]]; later parts of the castle were still in use as a County Court until early 2006 when a new [[Crown Court]]s building opened. A plaque near the ruined Norman gatehouse recalls the fate of [[Alice Molland]], tried for [[witchcraft]] at Exeter in 1685, and reputedly the last person in England to have been executed for that crime; others convicted of witchcraft had been hanged in Exeter in 1581, 1610, and 1682.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Stoyle|first1=Mark|title=It is but an old wytche gonne\u2019: Prosecution and Execution for Witchcraft in Exeter, 1558-1610|journal=History|date=April 2011|volume=96|issue=2|pages=129\u201351}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Sharpe|first1=James|title=Instruments of Darkness: Witchcraft in England, 1550-1750|date=1996|publisher=Hamish Hamilton|location=London|page=121}}</ref>\n* The [[Exeter Guildhall|Guildhall]], which has medieval foundations and has been claimed to be the oldest municipal building in England still in use.<ref>See for example: {{cite book|last=Hele's School Historical Society. |title=Exeter \u2013 Then and Now|year=1947|publisher=A. Wheaton & Co|page=31}}</ref>\n* Mol's Coffee House, a historic building in the Cathedral Close.\n* Tuckers' Hall, a fine old building that is still used for smart functions.\n* The [[Custom House, Exeter|Custom House]] in the attractive [[Exeter Quay|Quay area]], which is the oldest brick building surviving in the city.\n* \"The House That Moved\", a 14th-century [[Tudor style architecture|Tudor]] building, earned its name in 1961 when it was moved from its original location on the corner of Edmund Street in order for a new road to be built in its place. Weighing more than twenty-one tonnes, it was strapped together and slowly moved a few inches at a time to its present-day position.\n*[[Parliament Street, Exeter|Parliament Street]] in the city centre is one of the narrowest streets in the world.\n*The [[Butts Ferry]], an ancient [[cable ferry]] across the River Exe.\n*[[Wyvern Barracks]], a former artillery barracks, dates back to about 1800.<ref>{{NHLE|num=1109979|desc=Guard House and attached wall Wyvern Barracks|accessdate=18 April 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Higher Barracks, Exeter|Higher Barracks]], a former cavalry barracks, dates back to 1794.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_buildings/higher_barracks.php|title=The Higher Barracks, or Cavalry Barracks - Howell Road|publisher=Exeter memories|accessdate=9 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221084936/http://www.exetermemories.co.uk/em/_buildings/higher_barracks.php|archive-date=21 December 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*The [[Devon County War Memorial]] in the Cathedral Close, designed by [[Sir Edwin Lutyens]] and unveiled in 1922 by [[Edward VIII|Edward, Prince of Wales]].<ref>{{National Heritage List for England |num=1393228 |desc=Devon County War Memorial and Processional Way|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany of these are built in the local dark red [[sandstone]], which gives its name to the castle and the park that now surrounds it (Rougemont means red hill). The pavements on Queen Street are composed of the rock [[diorite]] and exhibit [[feldspar]] crystals, while those around Princesshay are composed of [[granodiorite]].\n\n===Northernhay Gardens===\nLocated just outside the castle, [[Northernhay Gardens]] is the oldest public open space in England, being originally laid out in 1612 as a pleasure walk for Exeter residents.\n\n==Transport==\n\n===Car===\n[[File:M5 Bridge crosses the River Exe - geograph.org.uk - 1109085.jpg|thumb|Bridge carrying the [[M5 motorway]] across the [[River Exe]]]]\nThe [[M5 motorway]] to [[Bristol]] and Exeter starts at [[Birmingham]], and connects at Bristol with the [[M4 motorway|M4]] to London and [[South Wales]]. The older [[A30 road]] provides a more direct route to London via the [[A303 road|A303]] and [[M3 motorway (Great Britain)|M3]]. The M5 is the modern lowest bridging point of the [[River Exe]]. Going westwards, the [[A38 road|A38]] connects Exeter to [[Plymouth]] and south east [[Cornwall]], whilst the A30 continues via [[Okehampton]] to north and west Cornwall. The cities of [[Bristol]], [[Plymouth]], [[Bath, Somerset|Bath]], [[Salisbury]] and [[Truro]] can all be reached within 2 hours.\n\nTravel by car in the city is often difficult with regular jams centred on the Exe Bridges area. Historically, the bridges were a significant bottleneck for holiday traffic heading to southwest England, leading to the construction of the first bypass in the mid-1930s over [[Countess Wear|Countess Wear Bridge]], followed by the M5 in 1977.<ref name=dcc>{{cite web|url=https://www.devonnewscentre.info/the-changing-face-of-bridge-road-in-exeter/|title=The changing face of Bridge Road in Exeter|publisher=Devon County Council|date=24 March 2016|accessdate=15 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161012100749/https://www.devonnewscentre.info/the-changing-face-of-bridge-road-in-exeter/|archive-date=12 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> To further address the problem of congestion in the city centre, [[Devon County Council]] has current park and ride services and is considering the introduction of [[congestion charge]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/6125042.stm|title=Drivers facing congestion charge|publisher=BBC News|date=7 November 2006|accessdate=13 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070216082313/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/devon/6125042.stm|archive-date=16 February 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Bus===\n{{refimprove section|date=September 2019}}\n\nExeter's main operator of local buses is [[Stagecoach South West]], which operates most of the services in the city. [[Dartline]] is a minor operator in the City. Former Cooks Coaches were taken over by [[Stagecoach Devon|Stagecoach]] forming Stagecoach South West. [[Western Greyhound]] was also a main operator connecting Exeter to Cornwall, [[Somerset]] and many different places in [[South West England]] until being taken over by [[First South West|First Devon & Cornwall]], [[Plymouth Citybus]] and [[Stagecoach South West]] in March 2015.\n\nThe High Street, pedestrianised except for bus and bicycle traffic, serves as the main hub for local buses. Country and express services operate from the city's bus station, in Paris Street, which intersects the High Street at its eastern end; some also call at [[Exeter St Davids railway station]] for direct connection to train services.\n\nCountry bus services, mostly operated by Stagecoach, run from Exeter to most places in East and [[North Devon]], but some are very infrequent. Regional express services run to [[Plymouth]], [[Torbay]], [[Bude]], and along the [[Jurassic Coast]] to [[Lyme Regis]]. [[National Express Coaches|National Express]] operates long-distance routes, for example to [[London Heathrow Airport|Heathrow]] and London.\n\n===Railway===\n[[File:2008 at Exeter St Davids - station frontage.jpg|thumb|Exeter St Davids Railway Station]]\n\nExeter is considered to be the main rail hub within the south-west and is linked to most branch lines in Devon, including to [[Riviera Line|Paignton]], [[Avocet Line|Exmouth]], [[Tarka Line|Barnstaple]] and [[Okehampton]] (by a special service). This makes it possible to reach most stations in Devon directly from [[Exeter St Davids railway station|Exeter St Davids]], although only during the summer months.\n\nExeter is served by three main railway stations. [[Exeter St Davids railway station|Exeter St Davids]] is served by all services and is a major [[interchange station]] within the [[South West Peninsula]]'s rail network, whilst [[Exeter Central railway station|Exeter Central]] is more convenient for the city centre but served only by local services and the main line route to London Waterloo. In the south-west of the city, [[Exeter St Thomas railway station|Exeter St Thomas]] serves the western side of the city. There are also six suburban stations, [[Topsham railway station|Topsham]], [[St James Park railway station|St James Park]], [[Polsloe Bridge railway station|Polsloe Bridge]], [[Pinhoe railway station|Pinhoe]], [[Digby and Sowton railway station|Digby & Sowton]] and [[Newcourt (Exeter) railway station|Newcourt]], served only by local services.\n\nThere are two main line railway routes from Exeter to London, the faster [[Reading to Taunton line|route via Taunton and Reading to London Paddington]] and the slower [[West of England Main Line]] via [[Salisbury, England|Salisbury]] and [[Basingstoke]] to [[London Waterloo railway station|London Waterloo]]. Another main line, the [[Cross Country Route]], links Exeter with [[Bristol]], [[Birmingham]], [[Derby]], [[Leeds]], [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[Edinburgh]] and [[Aberdeen]]. [[Great Western Railway (train operating company)|Great Western Railway]] and [[CrossCountry]] services continue westwards along the [[Exeter to Plymouth Line]], variously serving [[Torquay]], [[Plymouth]] and [[Cornwall]]. Local branch lines run to [[Paignton]] (see [[Riviera Line]]), [[Exmouth, Devon|Exmouth]] (see [[Avocet Line]]) and [[Barnstaple]] (see [[Tarka Line]]). There is also a summer weekend service to [[Okehampton]] for access to [[Dartmoor]].\n\nThe [[Exeter to Plymouth railway of the LSWR|Exeter to Plymouth line of the London and South Western Railway (LSWR)]] used to provide an alternative route via [[Okehampton]] connecting north [[Cornwall]] and [[Plymouth]] to Exeter and the rest of the UK railway system until its closure in 1968. There are proposals to reopen the line from Okehampton, Tavistock to Bere Alston for a through service to Plymouth.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Harris| first = Nigel| title = Taking trains back to Tavistock| journal = Rail| issue = 590| pages = 40\u201345| publisher = Bauer| year = 2008}}</ref> On the night of 4 February 2014, amid high winds and extremely rough seas, part of the [[South Devon Railway sea wall]] at Dawlish was breached, washing away around {{convert|40|m}} of the wall and the ballast under the railway immediately behind and closing the [[Exeter to Plymouth Line]]. [[Network Rail]] began repair work<ref>{{cite web|title=UK storms destroy railway line and leave thousands without power|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26042990|publisher=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=5 February 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140205072449/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-26042990|archive-date=5 February 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> and the line reopened on 4 April 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dawlish's storm-damaged railway line reopens|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-devon-26874503|accessdate=4 April 2014|work=BBC news|date=4 April 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140404063923/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-devon-26874503|archive-date=4 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> In the wake of widespread disruption caused by damage to the mainline track at [[Dawlish]] by coastal storms in February 2014, [[Network Rail]] are considering reopening the Bere Alston to Okehampton and Exeter section of the [[Exeter to Plymouth railway of the LSWR|former LSWR line]] as an alternative to the coastal route.<ref>{{cite web | title=Network Rail chooses Dawlish alternative route | publisher=BBC News | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26110559 | date=10 February 2014 | accessdate=10 February 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140211080406/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-26110559 | archive-date=11 February 2014 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Air===\n[[File:ExeterAirportUK.jpg|thumb|Exeter International Airport]]\n[[Exeter Airport]] lies east of the city, and the local airline, previously called [[Jersey European]] and [[British European]] but now known as [[Flybe]], is a significant local employer. It is also a base for [[Thomson Airways]] with flights to [[Faro Airport|Faro]], [[Mallorca]], [[Lanzarote]] and elsewhere. The airport offers a range of scheduled flights to British and Irish regional airports and [[Charter airline|charter]] flights. Connections to international hubs began with [[Paris-Charles de Gaulle]] in 2005 and later a daily service to [[Amsterdam Schiphol Airport]]. [[Ryanair]] started flights in 2019 to Luqa, Naples and Malaga.\n\n===Canal===\n[[File:Exeter Canal Basin - geograph.org.uk - 238695.jpg|thumb|Exeter Canal Basin]]\nThe [[Exeter Canal]], also known as the Exeter Ship Canal, was first constructed by John Trew in about 1566,<ref>{{cite book|first=Kenneth R.|last=Clew|title=The Exeter Canal|location=Chichester|publisher=Phillimore|year=1984|isbn=0-85033-544-2}}</ref> representing one of the oldest artificial waterways in Britain. It was cut to bypass the St James' Weir that had been built across the [[River Exe]] at Duckes Marsh to provide a leat to a mill constructed just below the confluence of the Northbrook, in what became the village of Countess Weir. The weir had the effect of preventing water-born trade in the City of Exeter and forced boats to load and unload at [[Topsham, Devon|Topsham]] from where the [[Earl of Devon|Earls of Devon]] were able to exact large tolls to transport goods to and from Exeter.\n\nOriginally 3 feet deep and 16 feet wide (0.9 m by 5 m), the canal ran {{convert|2.0|mi|2|abbr=out}} from the confluence of the Matford Brook, just above Bridge Road in [[Countess Wear|Countess Weir]] to Haven Banks, close to the centre of Exeter. In order to maintain a consistent navigable water level, another weir was constructed by Trew, just below the point the canal joins the river. The canal was later extended south to Topsham Lock {{convert|3.65|mi|2|abbr=out}}, deepened and widened, and later still it was extended to Turf Lock near [[Manor_of_Powderham|Powderham]] {{convert|5.0|mi|2|abbr=out}}. The canal was successful until the middle of the 19th century since when its use gradually declined \u2013 the last commercial use was in 1972. However it is now widely used for leisure purposes, and the city basin is part of a \u00a324&nbsp;million redevelopment scheme.\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of schools in Devon}}\n[[File:Laver Building, University of Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 148746.jpg|thumb|upright|Laver Building, University of Exeter]]\nThe [[University of Exeter]] has two campuses in the city, both notable for their attractive parkland.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} It is one of the largest employers in the city. The university includes the [[University of Exeter Business School|Business School]], the [[Bill Douglas Cinema Museum]], the [[Henry Wellcome]] building for Biocatalysis, and, as of September 2018, the Exeter Centre for [[Ellen MacArthur Foundation|Circular Economy]].\n\n[[Exeter College, Exeter|Exeter College]] is a [[further education]] college. It previously operated as the sole [[sixth form]] for the entire [[maintained school]] sector in the city. However, in 2014 [[Exeter Mathematics School]] was established, a [[Free school (England)|free school]] sixth form with a specialism in Mathematics.\n\nFor about 30 years the city of Exeter operated a [[maintained school]] system in which the divisions between phases came at different ages from most of the United Kingdom, with first, middle and high rather than infant, junior and secondary schools, so that children transferred between schools at the age of about 8 and 12 rather than 7 and 11.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} From 2005, however, it has adopted the more usual pattern, because of the pressures of the UK [[National Curriculum (England, Wales and Northern Ireland)|National Curriculum]]. The changeover back to the more typical structure led to a citywide, [[Private Finance Initiative|PFI]] funded, rebuilding programme for the high schools and led to the changing of names for some schools. Following the reorganisation there are 25 primary schools, four referral schools, three [[special school]]s and five secondary schools within Exeter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.devon.gov.uk/index/learning/schools/locations_and_details.htm|title=Schools, locations and details|work=Devon County Council website|accessdate=19 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080704151841/http://www.devon.gov.uk/index/learning/schools/locations_and_details.htm|archive-date=4 July 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> The secondary schools are [[Isca Academy]] (formerly Priory High School), [[St James School, Exeter|St James School]] (formerly St James High School), [[St Luke's Science and Sports College]] (formerly Vincent Thompson High School), [[St Peter's Church of England Aided School]] (a consolidation of the former Bishop Blackall High School for Girls and Heles High School for Boys), and [[West Exe School]] (formerly St Thomas High School).\n\nThe city has a number of independent schools, including [[Exeter School]], [[Exeter Cathedral School]], [[The Maynard School]], [[Bramdean School]], [[St Wilfrid's School, Exeter|St Wilfrid's School]] and [[Exeter Tutorial College]].\n\nThere are specialist schools for pupils with sensory needs, including Exeter Royal Academy for Deaf Education, and the West of England School for the Partially Sighted.\n\nThe Atkinson Unit is a secure specialist residential and educational complex for children in care or [[Detention of suspects|remanded]] by the courts.\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St Michael's church, and Episcopal building, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 287157.jpg|thumb|upright|St. Michael's Church and Episcopal Building]]\nNumerous churches, and other religious buildings, are present in Exeter. Of which a majority belong to differing Christian denominations, with the exception of an [[Church of England]] cathedral. The medieval city of Exeter had nearly 70 churches, chapels, monasteries and almshouses.<ref>Nicholas Orme ''The Churches of Medieval Exeter''. Exeter: Impress Books, 2014; back cover</ref>\n\n[[Exeter Cathedral]] is the seat of the [[Bishop of Exeter]]. The erection of the present building was completed in approximately 1400, and possesses the longest uninterrupted vaulted ceiling in England, as well as other noticeable characteristics. A collective of Anglican churches form the [[Deanery of Christianity (Exeter)|Exeter Deanery]].\n\nOn the other hand, the Catholic community of Exeter occupy two Churches, the [[Sacred Heart Church, Exeter|Sacred Heart]] and the [[Blessed Sacrament Church, Exeter|Blessed Sacrament]], with congregations reflecting the nature of older and more recent immigration.\n\n[[Exeter Synagogue]], located within a near proximity to Mary Arches Street, was completely erected in 1763.\n\nExeter's mosque and Islamic centre are located on York Road. The first mosque was opened in 1977.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tellingourstoriesexeter.org.uk/index.php?mact=News,cntnt01,detail,0&cntnt01articleid=18&cntnt01origid=57&cntnt01returnid=80|title=Telling our stories, finding our roots Exeter Multicultural History - Timeline|website=www.tellingourstoriesexeter.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> The purpose-built mosque opened in 2011.\n\nAt the [[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 census]], 69.12% of Exeter's population stated their religion as Christian, which is mildly lower than the regional average of 73.99% and the national average of 71.74%. Despite this, all other religions had exceeded the regional average at just under 1%. Although, they were much lower than the national average with the exemption of Buddhism. 20.45% of Exeter's population stated they had no religion, which was higher than the regional average of 16.75% and the national average of 14.59%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=276927&c=Exeter&d=13&e=15&g=436252&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1231680745917&enc=1&dsFamilyId=17|title=Religion|date=1 April 2001|work=[[United Kingdom Census 2001]]|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|accessdate=11 January 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110613050407/http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=276927&c=Exeter&d=13&e=15&g=436252&i=1001x1003x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1231680745917&enc=1&dsFamilyId=17|archive-date=13 June 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Anglican churches===\n[[File:St David's church, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 213553.jpg|thumb|St. David's Church, Exeter]]\n[[John Betjeman]] (writing in 1958) selects [[St David's Church, Exeter|St David's]] (\"[[W. D. Caroe|Caroe]]'s best church\"), [[St Martin's Church, Exeter|St Martin's]] (\"characteristic little city church, 15th century\"), [[Church of St Mary Steps,  Exeter|St Mary Steps]] (\"medieval city church; font\"), St Michael's (\"Victorian, on a fine site\"), and [[St Thomas' Church, Exeter|St Thomas's]] (\"fittings\"). His coverage of St Mary Arches is more detailed: \"worth seeing ... as the completest Norman church in Devon: beautifully light and airy after its restoration from the bombing in 1942. 18th-century altar arrangements. Memorials to Exeter worthies, 16th to 18th centuries.\"<ref>Betjeman, John, ed. (1968) ''Collins Pocket Guide to English Parish Churches; the South''. London: Collins; p. 164</ref>\n\nThe aforementioned collective of Anglican churches include St David's Church, located near to St. David's Station. The church was envisaged by [[W. D. Caroe]], with the windows being manufactured by Kempe & Tower, and was later constructed between 1897 and 1900. A tower stands on the northeast side, with the overall design being described as \u201chighly picturesque by Nikolaus Pevsner.\n\nSt Edmund-on-the-Bridge was built on the Exe Bridge ca. 1230\u201340. Two arches of the bridge remain under the undercroft though the church was rebuilt in the Perpendicular style in 1835, using the old materials.\n\nSt Martin's is in the [[Cathedral Close]]; the plan is odd, and there are numerous items of church furniture, though these are not of high aesthetic value. St Mary Arches is a Norman church with aisles. St Mary Steps was originally by the West Gate of the city; the font is Norman, and there is a remarkable early clock. St Michael, Heavitree was built in 1844\u201346 and extended later in the century. [[St Pancras Church, Exeter|St Pancras]] is of the 13th century and has a nave and chancel only; the font is Norman. The plan of [[St Petrocks Church, Exeter|St Petroc's]] church is highly unusual: a second chancel has been added facing north while the original chancel has another use and faces east. There are two aisles on the south, one of 1413 and another of the 16th century.\n\nSt Sidwell's church is by W. Burgess, 1812, in the Perpendicular style. [[St Stephens Church, Exeter|St Stephen's church]] is partly of the 13th century but most of the structure is as rebuilt in 1826.<ref>Pevsner, N. (1952) ''South Devon''. Harmondsworth: Penguin Books; pp. 148\u201353</ref> [[St Michael and All Angels Church, Exeter|St Michael and All Angels Church]] on Mount Dinham has a spire which exceeds the height of the towers of Exeter Cathedral.\n\n==Sport==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:St James Park Exeter City.jpg|thumb|[[St James Park (Exeter)|St James Park]], the home of [[Exeter City F.C.]]]] -->\n\n===Rugby Union===\n\nThe [[rugby union]] team [[Exeter Chiefs]] play their home games at [[Sandy Park]] stadium, located adjacent to junction 30 of the M5, and frequently achieve attendances of over 11,000 spectators. Sandy Park was constructed in September 2006 and cost \u00a315 million. Exeter Chiefs relocated there from their previous stadium at the County Ground which had been used continually from 1905.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Exeter Chiefs \u2013 History|url=http://www.exeterchiefs.co.uk/club-info/history/|accessdate=9 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307010105/http://www.exeterchiefs.co.uk/club-info/history/|archive-date=7 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nExeter Chiefs achieved promotion in the [[2009\u201310 RFU Championship|2009\u201310 season]] following concessive victories against [[Bristol Rugby|Bristol]] and have since remained within the highest division of English rugby, the [[Aviva Premiership]].<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn the [[2011\u201312 Aviva Premiership|2011\u201312 season]] of the Aviva Premiership, Exeter Chiefs  finished in fifth place, earning a spot in the [[Heineken Cup]]. Exeter Chiefs won their first piece of silverware when they defeated Northampton 15\u20138 at Sandy Park in the 2014 LV Cup final.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/26551754 |title=Cup final: Exeter Chiefs 15-8 Northampton Saints |last=Osborne |first=Chris |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=16 March 2014 |access-date=13 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150901102155/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/rugby-union/26551754 |archive-date=1 September 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Furthermore, Exeter Chiefs were crowned English champions in 2017, after defeating Wasps RFC in the Aviva Premiership final at Twickenham.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/40018239 |title=Premiership final: Wasps 20-23 Exeter Chiefs (aet) |last=Law |first=James |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=27 May 2017 |access-date=13 February 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829132950/http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/rugby-union/40018239 |archive-date=29 August 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> The city also has two other clubs: Wessex Rugby Club, which is located in Exwick, and Exeter Saracens Rugby Club,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exetersaracens.co.uk/|title=Exeter Saracens Rugby Football Club Website|accessdate=19 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080726193243/http://www.exetersaracens.co.uk/|archive-date=26 July 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> which is located in Whipton.\n\n===Football===\n\n[[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]] is Exeter's predominant Professional Association football club. They play their home games at St James Park, where they have remained since they were established in 1904. Originally, St James Park was a field used for fattening pigs. A redevelopment scheme was introduced in 2017, due to finish the year after, apparently providing a vastly increased fan experience.\n\nExeter City F.C became founder members of the [[Football League]]'s new [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] (south) in 1920, but have never progressed beyond the third tier of the English football league system. In 2003, Exeter City F.C were relegated to the [[Football Conference|Conference]] before reclaiming their Football League place in 2008 and achieving successive promotions to [[Football League One|League One]] in 2009. However, Exeter City F.C were relegated to League Two at the end of the 2011/12 season.\n\n===Cricket===\n\nExeter Cricket Club administer three teams that play in the Devon Cricket League. The first of which plays in the Premier Division at first XI level and the next plays at second XI level.\n\nExeter Cricket Club play their home games at Country Ground where they have remained for a period exceeding 180 years.\n\n===Rowing===\n\nExeter [[rowing (sport)|Rowing]] Club enjoys success both locally and nationally, and has a recorded history originating in the early 19th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeterrowingclub.com/general/history.php|title=History \u2013 Exeter Rowing Club|accessdate=15 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120925235856/http://www.exeterrowingclub.com/general/history.php|archive-date=25 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe City of Exeter Rowing Regatta is run annually in July, and is the eldest and largest regatta in the South West, with racing first recorded on the river in the 1860s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter-regatta.co.uk|title=About the regatta|accessdate=15 September 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819151025/http://www.exeter-regatta.co.uk/|archive-date=19 August 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Squash===\n\nThe Devon & Exeter [[Squash (sport)|Squash]] club is one of the most active squash clubs in the region, annually hosting the Exeter Diamonds.\n\n===Speedway===\n\nExeter's [[Motorcycle speedway|speedway]] team, [[Exeter Falcons]], was established in 1929 and were located at the County Ground until its permanent closure in 2005.\n\nIn a fixture during the 2004 season, they defeated [[Rye House Cobras|Rye House]] by the maximum score of 75\u201315.\n\nAt the site, Exeter Falcons member Jack Geran trained younger members in the art of the shale sport on a speedway training track in the late 1970s and early-1980s. Speedway was also staged briefly at tracks in [[Alphington, Devon|Alphington]] and Peamore after the Second World War.\n\nThe history of [[Motorcycle speedway|Speedway]] in Exeter up to the mid-1950s has been recorded in three books by Tony Lethbridge.\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Literature===\n[[File:Riddle-pyramid-comp.jpeg|thumb|upright|The Exeter Riddle Sculpture in Exeter High Street, created by artist Michael Fairfax and installed in 2005<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml|title=BBC - Devon Features|website=www.bbc.co.uk|access-date=2018-03-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504020912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml|archive-date=4 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\nThe ''[[Exeter Book]]'', an anthology of Anglo Saxon poetry, is conserved in the vaults of Exeter Cathedral. The Exeter Book originates from the 10th century and is one of four manuscripts that between them encompass all surviving poetry composed in [[Old English language|Old English]]. Predominantly, the Book incorporates shorter poems, several religious pieces, and a series of [[riddle]]s, a handful of which are famously [[lewd]]. A selection of the aforementioned riddles are inscribed on a highly polished steel obelisk situated in High Street, placed there on 30 March 2005.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml The Riddle of the new Exeter Statue] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080504020912/http://www.bbc.co.uk/devon/news_features/2005/riddles_statue.shtml |date=4 May 2008 }} (retrieved 19 November 2010)</ref>\n\nAnother famous piece of literature is the ''[[Exeter Domesday|Exon Domesday]]'', a composite land and tax register of 1086. The piece contains a variety of administrative materials concerning the counties of Cornwall, Devon, Dorset, Somerset and Wiltshire. This piece is also conserved in Exeter Cathedral.\n\nIn 2019, the city became a [[UNESCO]] [[City of Literature]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.exeter.gov.uk/exeter-only-uk-city-to-be-awarded-unesco-city-of-literature-status/|title=Exeter becomes City of Literature|access-date=31 October 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191031182330/https://news.exeter.gov.uk/exeter-only-uk-city-to-be-awarded-unesco-city-of-literature-status/|archive-date=31 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Theatre===\nNumerous theatres occupy Exeter. One of which is the [[Northcott Theatre]]. The Northcott Theatre is situated in the Streatham campus of the University of Exeter and is one of relatively few provincial English theatres to maintain its own [[repertory|repertory company]]. This theatre is the successor to the former [[Theatre Royal, Exeter]] which was permanently closed in 1962.\n\n[[File:Barnfield Theatre (geograph 4203993).jpg|thumb|left|Barnfield Theatre]]\nAnother popular theatre in Exeter is the [[Barnfield Theatre]]. Originally, the building was constructed as Barnfield Hall by Exeter Literary Society towards the end of the 19th century and converted in 1972. Currently, the theatre is a charity and is used as a venue for amateur and professional theatrical companies.\n\nThe Cygnet Theatre in Friars Walk is the home of the [[Cygnet Training Theatre]] and is a member of the [[Conference of Drama Schools]]. As well as performances given by students in training, this theatre also stages performances from visiting repertory companies and has a good reputation for quality events.\n\nThe Bike Shed Theatre and Cocktail Bar opened in September 2010 before permanently closing in March 2018. The Theatre was forced to close after failing to generate enough profit from the cocktail bar in order to operate the theatre. Fundamentally, the theatre offered intimate live music and performances and operated from basement premises in Fore Street.\n\nAdditionally, more innovative and contemporary performances, theatrical productions and dance pieces are programmed by Exeter Phoenix in Exeter City Centre and The Exeter Corn Exchange in Market Street.\n\n===Music===\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2010}}\nThere are two festivals each year, of all the arts but with a particular concentration of musical events: the annual \"Vibraphonic\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibraphonic2011.co.uk/|title=Vibraphonic 2011 website|work=Vibraphonic 2011 Festival website|access-date=5 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929144320/http://www.vibraphonic2011.co.uk/|archive-date=29 September 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> festival, held in March provides a fortnight of soul, blues, jazz, funk, reggae and electronic music.\n\nThe largest orchestra based in Exeter is the EMG Symphony Orchestra<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emgsymphonyorchestra.org|title=EMG Symphony Orchestra website|accessdate=19 July 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509124758/http://www.emgsymphonyorchestra.org/|archive-date=9 May 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> which frequently presents concerts at the University of Exeter and at Exeter Cathedral.\n\n[[Chris Martin]], who is lead singer of internationally famous band [[Coldplay]], grew up in Countess Wear in the south east of the city.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meritt |first1=Anita |title=Chris Martin and Exeter - why Coldplay dropped album exclusive in city paper |url=https://www.devonlive.com/whats-on/music-nightlife/chris-martin-exeter-coldplay-dropped-3461066 |website=Devon Live |accessdate=29 October 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191029030243/https://www.devonlive.com/whats-on/music-nightlife/chris-martin-exeter-coldplay-dropped-3461066 |archive-date=29 October 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===Museums and Galleries===\n* The [[Royal Albert Memorial Museum]] in Queen Street is Exeter's predominant museum. The museum maintains its own collections of regional, national and international importance. Recently, the museum underwent an extensive refurbishment. It reopened on 14 December 2011, and was subsequently awarded the National Art Fund Prize \u2013 UK Museum of the Year 2012.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal Albert Memorial Museum|url=http://www.rammuseum.org.uk/|work=RAM Museum Website|access-date=5 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713150413/http://www.rammuseum.org.uk/|archive-date=13 July 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> The Museum also runs St Nicholas Priory in Mint Lane, near Fore Street. \n* Additionally, the University of Exeter has an extensive fine art collection and an assortment of exhibition spaces across its Streatham campus. Showing a vibrant programme of exhibitions, performances, films and visual arts. The sculpture collection contains works by artists including Barbara Hepworth, Peter Thursby, Geoffrey Clark and Elaine M. Goodwin. It can be located using the Sculpture Trail. \n*Exeter Phoenix is one of South West England's leading contemporary arts venues. The venue occupies the former university site in Gandy Street and programmes international, national and outstanding regional artists.\n* Until its closure in 2017, [[Spacex (art gallery)]], was a contemporary arts organisation, that programmed exhibitions of contemporary art and promoted artist-led projects, events and research.\n\n===Newspapers===\n* ''[[Express and Echo]]'', twice-weekly with a Monday and Thursday edition.\n* ''[[Trewman's Exeter Flying Post|Exeter Flying Post]]'', published weekly. Originally discontinued in 1917, but was revived in 1976 as an alternative community magazine. The last issue was in 2012. \n* ''The [[Western Morning News]]'', a [[Plymouth]] printed daily regional paper. \n* ''[[Exepos\u00e9]]'', the University's student newspaper, printed fortnightly.\n\n===Radio===\n[[BBC Radio Devon]] broadcasts to Exeter locally on FM (95.8) and AM (990 AM/MW), although the majority of programming originates in Plymouth. In the evenings, BBC Radio Devon joins the South West Regional service. [[Heart South West]], formerly [[Gemini FM]] and [[Devonair]], broadcasts on 97.0 FM, with [[East Devon]] and [[Torbay]] utilising their own frequencies. Both Heart South West and BBC Devon broadcast from the St. Thomas transmitter. AM radio is broadcast from Pearce's Hill located at J31 of the M5.\n\nOther radio stations include [[Exeter FM]], an easy listening station broadcasting on 107.3 FM, Phonic.FM which provides a \"no adverts no playlist\" alternative on 106.8 FM or online at www.phonic.fm, VI, a station broadcasting from the West of England School and College on 1386 AM/MW.\n\nAdditionally, Exeter University has a well established student station, [[Xpression FM]], which broadcasts on 87.7 FM using two low-powered transmitters, although it can be heard over much of the north of the city.\n\nThe local [[commercial radio]] station is [[107.3 Radio Exe|Radio Exe]]. The local [[community radio]] station is [[Phonic FM]].\n\n===Television===\nBoth [[BBC Spotlight]] and [[ITV West Country]] provide Exeter with regional news outputs. BBC Spotlight is broadcast from Plymouth and ITV Westcountry is broadcast from Bristol. Although, both services do have newsrooms in Exeter. The St Thomas and [[Stockland Hill transmitting station]] both provide the city's coverage with both transmitters having completed the [[digital switchover]].\n\n===Twin towns===\n[[File:Piazza Terracina, Exeter - geograph.org.uk - 236121.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Piazza Terracina, Exeter, named after [[Terracina]], Italy]]\nExeter is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with [[Rennes]] in France,<ref name=\"Archant twinning 3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130705094933/http://www.completefrance.com/language-culture/twin-towns|title=British towns twinned with French towns ''[via WaybackMachine.com]''|accessdate=20 July 2013|archivedate=5 July 2013|work=Archant Community Media Ltd}}</ref> [[Bad Homburg]] in Germany, [[Yaroslavl]] in Russia, and [[Terracina]] in Italy.<ref name=\"Exeter twinning\">{{cite web|url=http://www.exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=9787|title=Town twinning|publisher=Exeter City Council|accessdate=16 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024180740/http://exeter.gov.uk/index.aspx?articleid=9787|archivedate=24 October 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Devon}}\n*[[Exeter (HM Prison)]]\n*[[Henry Phillpotts]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources and further reading==\n{{See also|Timeline of Exeter#Bibliography|l1=Bibliography of the history of Exeter}}\n{{refbegin|2}}\n*{{cite book\n|last=Gray\n|first=Todd\n|title=Exeter: The Traveller's Tales\n|year=2000\n|isbn=1-903356-00-8\n|publisher=The Mint Press\n|location=Exeter}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Higham\n|first= Robert\n|title= Making Anglo-Saxon Devon\n|publisher=The Mint Press\n|year= 2008\n|location= Exeter\n|isbn= 978-1-903356-57-9}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Hoskins\n|first= W. G.\n|authorlink= William George Hoskins\n|title= Two Thousand Years in Exeter\n|publisher=Phillimore\n|location= Chichester\n|year= 2004\n|edition= Revised and updated\n|page= 23\n|isbn= 1-86077-303-6}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Sellman\n|first= R.R.\n|title= Aspects of Devon History\n|publisher=Devon Books\n|location= Exeter\n|year= 1985\n|edition= New\n|isbn= 0-86114-756-1}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Sharp\n|first= Thomas\n|authorlink= Thomas Wilfred Sharp\n|title=Exeter Phoenix: A Plan for Rebuilding\n|year=1946\n|publisher=The Architectural Press\n|location=London}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Stoyle\n|first= Mark\n|authorlink = Mark Stoyle\n|title=Circled With Stone: Exeter's City Walls, 1485\u20131660\n|year=2003\n|publisher=University of Exeter Press\n|location=Exeter\n|isbn= 978-0-85989-727-3}}\n*{{cite book\n|last= Stoyle\n|first= Mark\n|title=From Deliverance to Destruction: Rebellion and Civil War in an English City\n|year=1996\n|publisher=Uni